window.__INITIAL_DATA__ = {"projects":[{"id":"project-1","folderName":"Project_1_Student_Resource_Hub","name":"Project 1 Student Resource Hub","faq":"# Student Resource & Academic Support Hub — FAQ\n\n**Q: Why should I trust this is actually free? Where is the budget coming from?** A: The platform is built using free, open-source technology and run locally. Council funds are strictly reserved for actual student research grants, not for hosting fees or expensive software licenses. We do not monetize your data or charge access fees.\n\n**Q: What if the Shared Flashcard Library has wrong answers and causes me to fail an exam?** A: The flashcards are peer-reviewed study tools. Every card features a 'Report Error' button. Any card flagged three times is automatically hidden until reviewed and corrected by the Academics Committee. However, these are supplementary aids and should not replace your official course materials.\n\n**Q: What happens if a professor refuses to follow the Syllabus Transparency Portal format?** A: The standardized syllabus format is backed by a written agreement with the College Dean's Office. If a professor refuses to comply, students can use the Centralized Grievance Channel to report the non-compliance. The council will then mediate the issue directly with the administration on the student's behalf.\n\n**Q: Isn't this just a glorified link-tree that duplicates things the university already offers?** A: The university does not offer a unified academic pathing tool, a localized research job board, or an integrated scholarship calculator that accurately accounts for specific student ID formats. This platform centralizes fragmented resources and builds the critical tools the administration has left empty.\n\n**Q: How do we know the contact numbers and procedures in the COS Student Survival Guide are actually updated and reliable?** A: All information regarding shifting, enlistment, and grievances is cross-verified directly with the Dean’s Office and respective departments at the beginning of every term by the Director for Academics to ensure nothing is outdated.","description":"# Project Description\n\nOne website that holds everything a student needs to stay enrolled, funded, and on track. If it helps a student survive the semester, it lives here.","executionPlan":"## **Project 1: Student Resource & Academic Support Hub**\n\n### **Execution Plan**\n\n**Quick classification note:** Every sub-feature here is Bucket B for ongoing operations. That said, the initial platform launch qualifies as a Website/Social Media Launch under the DAAM Types of Activity, which routes through SLIFE with a 5-8 day lead time. Dir. Documentations files this before any public announcement goes out. After the launch SLIFE clears, individual sub-feature rollouts each go through P&M clearance (24-hour lead time) separately. \n\n* * *\n\n### **RACI Matrix**\n\n| Sub-Feature | Responsible | Accountable | Consulted | Informed |\n| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |\n| COS Student Information Hub | Dir. Academics | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| Scholarship Grade Calculator | Dir. Academics | President | Chief of Staff, Dir. Finance | Dir. Documentations |\n| Academic Pathing Tool | Dir. Academics | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| Syllabus Transparency Portal | Dir. Academics | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| Note Generator | Dir. Academics | President | Dir. Creatives | Dir. Documentations |\n| Free Software Directory | Dir. Academics | President |  | Dir. Documentations |\n| LaTeX Tutorials | Dir. Academics | President |  | Dir. Documentations |\n| NMAT Online Repository | Dir. Academics | President |  | Dir. Documentations |\n| Research Grants & Funding Portal | Dir. R\\&D | President | Chief of Staff, Dir. Finance | Dir. Documentations |\n| Research Job Board | Dir. R\\&D | President | Dir. EXT/INT | Dir. Documentations |\n| Research Readiness Survey | Dir. R\\&D | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| P\\&M for all sub-features | Dir. Creatives | Chief Communications |  | Dir. Documentations |\n| All clearance and submission tracking | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff |  |  |\n\n* * *\n\n### **Proposed Timeline**\n\nThis runs in two phases. Phase 1 is every academic survival tool. Phase 2 is the research tools.\n\n**Pre-Launch (6 Weeks Before Term Start)**\n\nThe real work happens here. Waiting until term starts to chase the Syllabus LOA or ADSO confirmation is too late.\n\n*   **T-6 weeks:** Pauline initiates the LOA request to the College Dean for the Syllabus Transparency Portal. This is the longest dependency and the only feature that cannot go live without a signature.\n*   **T-5 weeks:** Dir. Academics contacts ADSO directly to confirm current scholarship retention criteria. Written confirmation only. A verbal answer is not enough.\n*   **T-4 weeks:** Web platform build starts. Dir. Academics inputs initial data: flowcharts, scholarship rules, department contacts for the Info Hub.\n*   **T-2 weeks:** Dir. Documentations submits the SLIFE pre-activity for the platform launch. 5-8 day lead time. This needs to clear before any public announcement goes out — P&M for individual sub-features is filed alongside it but the SLIFE is the gate.\n*   **T-2 weeks:** Dir. Creatives submits batched P&M clearances for all Phase 1 sub-features. Submitting early leaves room for revisions without cutting into the 24-hour minimum.\n*   **T-1 week:** Dir. Academics and Dir. R&D sign off on data accuracy. Platform is ready before Day 1 of term.\n\n**Phase 1 Launch (Week 1 of Term)**\n\n*   **Day 1-3:** COS Student Information Hub, Scholarship Calculator, Academic Pathing Tool, Note Generator, Free Software Directory, LaTeX Tutorials, and NMAT Repository go live. GOSM posting follows immediately after P&M clears.\n*   **Day 3-5:** Syllabus Transparency Portal goes live once the written LOA is signed. This feature does not launch without it.\n\n**Phase 2 Launch (Weeks 2-3 of Term)**\n\n*   **Week 2:** Dir. Creatives submits P&M for the Grants Portal and Job Board. Dir. EXT/INT is looped in to push the Job Board to any external research contacts.\n*   **Week 2-3:** Research Grants Portal and Research Job Board go live after clearances confirm. \n*   **Week 3:** Research Readiness Survey launches alongside the Job Board. Dir. R&D monitors responses and starts drafting a data summary for the admin.\n\n**Ongoing Maintenance**\n\n*   **Monthly:** Dir. Academics re-verifies Calculator and Pathing Tool data against any ADSO or Registrar updates. The \"Last Verified\" timestamp on each tool updates to reflect this.\n*   **End of Term:** Dir. R&D compiles Research Readiness Survey results and submits a brief report to the administration, with a formal RESAP recommendation if the data supports one.\n\n**Blackout Compliance**\n\n*   GOSM Defense Week (Jan 19-24): No new sub-feature launches. Phase 1 should already be live by this point.\n*   Midterms (Feb 16-21): All promotional pushes pause. Platform stays live and operational.\n*   ILW (Mar 2-7): Same rule. Promotion pauses, platform runs.\n*   Activity Ban (Mar 30 - Apr 11): Unaffected. This is a standing platform, not an activity.\n\n* * *\n\n### **Dependencies**\n\nIn order of urgency. The first two are the only real blockers. Everything else can run in parallel.\n\n1.  **Syllabus Portal LOA from the Dean's Office (critical path):** Dir. Academics prepares the letter, Pauline signs and submits. Target: signed at least 3 weeks before term start. If this is delayed, the portal launch slides accordingly.\n2.  **ADSO scholarship criteria (written confirmation):** Dir. Academics establishes a recurring contact at ADSO and requests written confirmation at the start of every term. The Calculator carries a public \"Last Verified\" date so students can see how current the data is.\n3.  **P&M clearance for each sub-feature:** Dir. Creatives batches these during pre-launch so all Phase 1 features are cleared before Day 1.\n4.  **Web platform and data verification:** All tools built and tested before term starts. Dir. Academics confirms academic data accuracy. Dir. Creatives confirms genesis-DESIGN compliance before anything goes public.\n5.  **Research Job Board vetting standards:** Dir. R&D and Dir. EXT/INT agree on a posting checklist before the board goes live. No listing is published without a review.","subprojects":"# Project 1: Student Resource & Academic Support Hub Sub-Projects\n\n## COS Student Information Hub\n\n*   **Description:** Everything you need to navigate college life in one place: Enlistment and pre-enlistment guides, shifting procedures, department policies, a full contact list for every department office and head, and an FAQ section built from the questions students actually ask. No more chasing down information across five different people and three Facebook groups.\n\n## Research Grants & Funding Portal\n\n*   **Description:** A working directory of every internal and external grant available, so students are never left guessing where to look for money.\n\n## Research Job Board\n\n*   **Description:** Professors and researchers, both inside DLSU and abroad, can post real research and apprenticeship openings here, giving students without existing connections an actual way in.\n\n## Research Readiness Survey\n\n*   **Description:** A short, recurring check asking students if they feel prepared for research work, so the council knows when to push for better orientation, and a consensus whether RESAP could be needed, instead of assuming, sending them directly through the administration.\n\n## Scholarship Grade Calculator\n\n*   **Description:** Lets scholars calculate exactly what grades they need to keep their scholarship, using the real criteria of their specific scholarship.\n\n## Academic Pathing Tool\n\n*   **Description:** A flowchart that can be interacted with, that shows students exactly what happens to their course load if they fail a class, and gives them an alternate path forward they request to bring straight to the administration for options.\n\n## Syllabus Transparency Portal (Approved by the Administration)\n\n*   **Description:** A standard syllabus format required for every class, so students wanting to study in advance could do so.\n\n## Note Generator\n\n*   **Description:** Even with good intentions such as studying, using AI online can still damage our environment. This is A free tool to convert your notes to flashcards, using locally-run, meaning, no environmental damage AI models, so reviewing for an exam doesn't depend on being able to afford a tutor, nor affecting our environment. Data is also yours, not used by datacenters.\n\n## Free Software Directory\n\n*   **Description:** A list of free, legitimate alternatives to the expensive software students are often buying for their hobbies or academics.\n\n## LaTeX tutorials\n\n*   **Description:** A step-by-step beginner guide on how to write anything math.\n\n## NMAT Online Repository\n\n*   **Description:** A collection of guides, academic notes, and shared experiences among real lasallians who took NMAT to give tips on how to ace the exam."},{"id":"project-2","folderName":"Project_2_Semana_ng_Siyensya","name":"Project 2 Semana ng Siyensya","faq":"# Frequently Asked Questions\n\n### Where exactly do the merchandise profits go?\n\nEvery single peso of profit from the Department Merchandise Drive is directly injected into the Financial Transparency Ledger. The funds are split between the Food Security Pantry to restock essential goods and the Emergency Micro-Grant to provide immediate cash assistance to scholars in need.\n\n### Are the academic incentives guaranteed for Wednesday's competitions?\n\nThe council is actively pushing a formal resolution to the Dean's Office to secure official plus-points or excused absences for participants and winners. We will not announce incentives until we have written approval from the Department Chairs to ensure no student's time is wasted.\n\n### How are the Discord Gaming Night brackets monitored?\n\nThe brackets are strictly scheduled for Saturday to ensure they do not bleed into your Sunday rest day before Midterms. Student volunteer marshals will enforce match start times and strictly penalize delays to keep the event running efficiently.","description":"# Project Description\n\nOne week, two events, and a merchandise drive that funds everything. Wednesday is academic competitions: Quiz Bee, On the Spot Research Making, and a Scientific Terminologies Spelling Bee, with faculty coordination underway for possible academic incentives. Saturday is the COS Discord Gaming Night, with Valorant, Deadlock, and MLBB brackets for students who want a night outside the lab. Department merch for Physics, Chemistry, Biology, Math, and Statistics runs the full week, with all proceeds going to the Food Security Pantry and Emergency Micro-Grant.","executionPlan":"## **Project 2: Semana ng Siyensya**\n\n### **Execution Plan**\n\n**Classification note:** All three sub-events are Bucket A. Academic Competitions need a General Pre-Activity (APS) form with a 4-6 day lead time. The Gaming Night is a Tournament, which routes through SLIFE (5-8 day lead time), not APS. The Merchandise Drive needs a Special Approval Slip (SCT) with a 1-3 day lead time. Every promotional material across the week goes through P&M clearance first (24 hours). Note: all financial transactions in this project require specimen signatures on file with OTREAS and the Treasurer's Exam passed by Dir. Finance. See Project 6 pre-launch checklist. Nothing moves without both.\n\nIf the Gaming Night runs a paid entry bracket — teams pay to join, winner takes a portion of the pool — here is how that processes financially. Entry fees collected from participants go into the DF via Deposit Slip (14-day lead time after the last transaction). The prize payout to the winning team is processed under GL Code 519004001 (Tokens, Awards and Prices). Net proceeds after the prize payout sit in the DF as fundraising income. If net profit after all expenses exceeds ₱5,000, a full FRA Report is required within one week of the event's conclusion. Prize recipients must be identified by full name and DLSU ID number on the payment document.\n\n**Recommended event window: March 9-15.** This clears Midterms (Feb 16-21), ILW (Mar 2-7), and lands comfortably before the Activity Ban (Mar 30). It also gives the most runway for faculty coordination and merchandise production without competing with exam season.\n\n* * *\n\n### **RACI Matrix**\n\n| Area | Responsible | Accountable | Consulted | Informed |\n| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |\n| Overall Event Coordination | Chief of Operations | President | Chief of Staff | All Directors |\n| Academic Competitions (Wed) | Dir. Academics | Chief of Staff | Dir. Logistics | Dir. Documentations |\n| Faculty Incentive Coordination | Dir. Academics | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| Merchandise Design | Dir. Creatives | Chief Communications | Dir. Finance | Dir. Documentations |\n| Merchandise Pre-Order & Sales | Dir. Finance | Chief of Operations | Dir. Creatives | President |\n| SCT Processing (Merchandise) | Dir. Finance | Chief of Operations | Dir. Documentations | President |\n| Discord Gaming Night (Sat) | Dir. EXT/INT | Chief Communications | Dir. Logistics | Dir. Documentations |\n| Venue Booking (both events) | Dir. Logistics | Chief of Operations | Dir. Academics | Dir. Documentations |\n| All Pre-Act Submissions | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Operations | Dir. Logistics | All Directors |\n| All P\\&M and Promotion | Dir. Creatives | Chief Communications | Dir. EXT/INT | Dir. Documentations |\n| Budget Tracking and Proceeds | Dir. Finance | Chief of Operations | President | Chief of Staff |\n\n* * *\n\n### **Proposed Timeline**\n\n**T-8 Weeks (8 Weeks Before Event Week)**\n\nFaculty coordination starts here. This is the longest dependency and the one most likely to slip if left late. Dir. Academics sends formal letters to department chairs proposing academic incentives for Wednesday's competitions. The exact form of incentive (extra credit, class standing points, attendance consideration) depends on each professor, so starting early gives time for back-and-forth without pressure.\n\nDir. Finance also draws up a budget draft at this point, covering projected merchandise production costs, venue fees, and a conservative sales estimate for the pre-order system.\n\n**T-6 Weeks**\n\nVenue booking for both Wednesday and Saturday goes to Dir. Logistics. Per the handover notes, college approval must be secured at minimum 30 days out. Going at 6 weeks gives a buffer if the first venue falls through.\n\nDir. Creatives starts working on five department merchandise designs: Physics, Chemistry, Biology, Math, and Statistics. Designs need to be final before pre-orders open, not after.\n\n**T-5 Weeks**\n\nIf merch production costs will exceed ₱10,000, Dir. Finance files the SPF at this point — one week before any supplier transaction — with quotations attached. GForm pre-order responses must be attached to the SPF per OTREAS requirements. The SCT at T-4 is separate.\n\nPre-order system opens once designs are finalized. A pre-order model is non-negotiable here. It prevents overstocking, guarantees profit margins, and lets Dir. Finance forecast actual proceeds before production costs are committed.\n\n**T-4 Weeks**\n\nDir. Documentations submits the APS Pre-Act for the Academic Competitions (4-6 day lead time) and the SLIFE pre-activity for the Gaming Night Tournament (5-8 day lead time) at the same time. They are separate submissions even though they go in the same week. At 4 weeks out, there is plenty of room to resubmit if something comes back with corrections, without risking a blackout window overlap.\n\nDir. Finance submits the SCT for merchandise sales at the same time.\n\nDir. EXT/INT sets up the Discord server infrastructure for the gaming night. Bracket systems for Valorant, Deadlock, MLBB, and Genshin need to be decided and tested before registration opens.\n\n**T-3 Weeks**\n\nPre-Act approvals should be back by now. If any come back rejected, Dir. Documentations flags it immediately to the Chief of Operations and resubmits same day.\n\nGaming Night registration opens publicly. Dir. Creatives pushes the first promotional materials after P&M clears.\n\n**T-2 Weeks**\n\nMajor promotion push across all channels. Pre-order deadline set at this point so production can start with confirmed numbers.\n\nDir. Academics confirms which faculty have agreed to incentivize participation and communicates this in the event promotion so students know about it before deciding to join.\n\n**T-1 Week**\n\nMerchandise in production or confirmed for pickup. Dir. Finance confirms proceeds projection and reports to President.\n\nFinal headcounts for Academic Competitions and Gaming Night. Dir. Logistics confirms all equipment, tables, and setup needs are in place for both venues.\n\n**Event Week: March 9-15**\n\n*   Monday to Friday: Merchandise Drive runs all week at a visible, high-traffic location.\n*   Wednesday: Academic Competitions (Quiz Bee, On the Spot Research Making, Science Terminologies Spelling Bee).\n*   Saturday: COS Discord Gaming Night.\n\nWednesday and Saturday are also when merch gets the hardest promotional push since foot traffic is highest on both days.\n\n**T+5 Days (Post-Event)**\n\nDir. Finance tabulates total proceeds and posts the split to the Transparency Ledger publicly: one portion to the Emergency Micro-Grant Fund, one to the Food Security Pantry. The Ledger update goes out after FAO confirms all receipts are processed, not when the event closes. Same sequencing as P6 and P8. Dir. Documentations submits Post-Activity (ADM) forms within the 5-day window.\n\n**Blackout Compliance**\n\nEvent week of March 9-15 clears all calendar constraints. ILW ends March 7. Activity Ban starts March 30. Pre-Act submissions at T-4 weeks fall in the first week of February, well outside Midterms.\n\n* * *\n\n### **Dependencies**\n\n1.  **Faculty confirmation for academic incentives:** No incentive can be advertised until at least two or three professors have confirmed in writing. Dir. Academics chases this from T-8 weeks. If no faculty confirms by T-4 weeks, the promotions still go out, just without the incentive angle. Do not delay promotion waiting for a confirmation that might not come.\n    \n2.  **Venue approval from college (minimum 30 days out):** Covers both the Wednesday competition venue and the Saturday gaming setup. If physical space for the gaming night is unavailable, the Saturday event defaults to fully online through Discord, which needs to be a pre-decided fallback, not a last-minute pivot.\n    \n3.  **Merchandise designs finalized before pre-orders open:** Dir. Creatives cannot hand off to the pre-order system with placeholder designs. Pre-orders open once all five department designs are confirmed and approved by Pauline.\n    \n4.  **APS Pre-Acts cleared before any event-specific promotion goes live:** P&M clearance for general awareness posts can happen earlier. But event-specific promotional materials (with a confirmed date, venue, and mechanic) need the Pre-Acts approved first.\n    \n5.  **SCT for merchandise processed before sales begin:** The Drive cannot open without it. Dir. Finance files this at T-4 weeks alongside the Pre-Acts.\n    \n6.  **Proceeds posted publicly within one week of the event:** Dir. Finance gives Dir. Documentations the final figures. Dir. Creatives posts the proceeds summary on the Transparency Ledger and on social media. This is a public accountability moment, not an internal memo.","subprojects":"# Project 2: Semana ng Siyensya Sub-Projects\n\n## Academic Competitions (Wednesday)\n\n*   **Description:** Quiz Bee, On the Spot Research Making, and Science Terminologies Spelling Bee. Open to all COS students, with possible academic incentives being coordinated with faculty.\n\n## Department Merchandise Drive (All Week)\n\n*   **Description:** Five department lines covering Physics, Chemistry, Biology, Math, and Statistics. All proceeds go directly to the micro-grant and disaster relief pools.\n\n## COS Discord Gaming Night (Saturday)\n\n*   **Description:** Valorant, Deadlock, and MLBB, Genshin competitions and co-op for COS students who want one night that has nothing to do with a deadline."},{"id":"project-3","folderName":"Project_3_Transparency_Platform","name":"Project 3 Transparency Platform","faq":"# Transparency & Accountability Platform — FAQ\n\n**Q: Why should I trust this is actually free?** A: The platform is built using free, open-source technology. Not a single peso of council funds goes into hosting or maintenance—all council money is strictly reserved for emergency relief and research grants, which you can verify yourself in real-time on our Financial Transparency Ledger.\n\n**Q: What stops the council from just deleting negative feedback from the Suggestion Tab?** A: Our explicit moderation policy forbids deleting substantive policy criticism. Posts are only removed if they contain personal harassment or hate speech against identifiable individuals. Furthermore, any removal requires two officers to jointly sign off, and the deletion action is logged internally.\n\n**Q: What if the admin completely ignores a grievance filed through your channel?** A: We will not lie to you: the council cannot force the administration to act. However, we can make their inaction visible. With your explicit consent, cases where the administration ignores a mediation outcome will be published on our public Ledger to apply direct visibility pressure.\n\n**Q: You're demanding transparency from the admin, but how do we know the council isn't hiding its own mistakes?** A: We hold ourselves to the exact same standard. Any grievance filed against an SCG officer bypasses the council entirely and goes straight to an external faculty ombudsperson or OSA. Furthermore, every council expenditure over ₱500 is publicly posted within 72 hours, naming the exact officer who approved it.","description":"# Project Description\n\nA platform that holds the council to the same standard it asks of the administration.","executionPlan":"## **Project 3: Transparency & Accountability Platform**\n\n### **Execution Plan**\n\n**Classification note:** All four sub-features are Bucket B for ongoing operations. The initial platform launch is a Website/Social Media Launch under the DAAM Types of Activity and routes through SLIFE (5-8 day lead time) before any public rollout. After that clears, individual feature announcements each go through P&M clearance (24-hour lead time) and GOSM posting clearance before going public. The Grievance Channel has one additional dependency that every other sub-feature does not: an external mediator must be identified and confirmed before it goes live.\n\n* * *\n\n### **RACI Matrix**\n\n| Sub-Feature | Responsible | Accountable | Consulted | Informed |\n| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |\n| Centralized Grievance Channel | Dir. Student Services | President | Chief of Staff, Dir. Finance | Dir. Documentations |\n| External Mediator Coordination | Chief of Staff | President | Dir. Student Services | Dir. Documentations |\n| Financial Transparency Ledger | Dir. Finance | Chief of Operations | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| Student Rights Charter | Chief of Staff | President | Dir. Student Services | Dir. Documentations |\n| Suggestion Tab | Dir. Student Services | President | Dir. Creatives | Dir. Documentations |\n| Moderation Policy (Suggestion Tab) | Dir. Student Services | President | Chief of Staff | All Directors |\n| P\\&M for all sub-features | Dir. Creatives | Chief Communications |  | Dir. Documentations |\n| All clearance and submission tracking | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff |  |  |\n| Ledger updates (ongoing) | Dir. Finance | Chief of Operations |  | President |\n| Grievance case mediation | Dir. Student Services | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n\n* * *\n\n### **Proposed Timeline**\n\n**T-6 Weeks (Before Term Start)**\n\nChief of Staff begins identifying the external mediator for the Grievance Channel. This is the most sensitive dependency in the entire platform. The mediator must be either a faculty ombudsperson or an OSA representative, and they need to agree in writing before the channel accepts a single submission. Without this, the Grievance Channel does not open. Dir. Student Services drafts the initial reach-out letter. Pauline signs it.\n\nAt the same time, Chief of Staff drafts the Student Rights Charter. This is a document, not a digital tool, so it does not need web development time. It does need to be reviewed carefully for accuracy before it goes anywhere near a student. Dir. Student Services reviews the draft against actual DLSU student handbook provisions so nothing in the charter contradicts or overpromises what the university's own rules already guarantee.\n\n**T-4 Weeks**\n\nExternal mediator confirmation should be in hand by now. If it is not, Chief of Staff escalates to Pauline and the two of them pursue it directly. The Grievance Channel launch date moves with this confirmation, not ahead of it.\n\nDir. Finance sets up the Transparency Ledger structure. The ledger needs a clear, consistent format before it goes public: date, item, amount, approving officer, status. Dir. Finance also establishes the internal rule that any expenditure over ₱500 gets posted within 72 hours of approval. This rule goes into the Comms Protocol so it is not optional.\n\nDir. Student Services drafts the Suggestion Tab moderation policy. Two things need to be decided before launch: what qualifies as a personal attack that gets moderated (and therefore requires two-officer sign-off to remove), and what counts as policy criticism that stays up regardless of how uncomfortable it is. This gets written down, not kept informal.\n\n**T-2 Weeks**\n\nDir. Documentations submits the SLIFE pre-activity for the platform launch (5-8 day lead time). This goes in before P&M so the two clear around the same time and the launch does not get held up waiting on one of them.\n\nDir. Creatives submits batched P&M clearances for all four sub-features. Student Rights Charter goes through a final read by Chief of Staff and Dir. Student Services before it is handed to Dir. Creatives for design.\n\nWeb platform build is finalized. Dir. Student Services and Dir. Finance do a full walkthrough of the Grievance Channel and Ledger before anything goes public. The Suggestion Tab is tested with internal submissions first to confirm the reply workflow actually works end to end.\n\n**T-1 Week**\n\nExternal mediator agreement is confirmed and filed with Dir. Documentations. This document needs to exist before the channel opens. Dir. Documentations logs it in the clearance tracker.\n\nAll P&M clearances should be back by now. GOSM posting clearance requested.\n\n**Week 1 of Term: Platform Launch**\n\nAll four features go live together. Launching them separately creates confusion about what the platform actually is. The Ledger goes live first, on Day 1, because it starts generating entries the moment the council makes any financial decision. The Grievance Channel, Rights Charter, and Suggestion Tab follow by Day 3 once GOSM clears.\n\n**Ongoing Operations**\n\n*   **Within 72 hours of any expenditure over ₱500:** Dir. Finance posts to the Ledger with the approving officer named. No exceptions, including during Midterms and ILW. The platform stays operational through all blackout windows since it is not an activity.\n*   **Weekly:** Dir. Student Services checks the Suggestion Tab for new submissions. Every submission gets a reply. If a student wants to lead their own idea, Dir. Student Services brings it to Pauline directly.\n*   **Per grievance filed:** Dir. Student Services logs it, loops in the external mediator, and keeps the student informed of status. If the grievance is against an SCG officer, it goes to the external mediator immediately without passing through the council first.\n*   **End of Term:** Dir. Finance reconciles the Ledger and publishes a term summary. Dir. Student Services compiles a Grievance and Suggestion report for Pauline: how many filed, how many resolved, how many suggestions received a response.\n\n**Blackout Compliance**\n\nThis platform is not event-based. It runs through Midterms, ILW, and the Activity Ban without interruption. The only things that pause during blackout windows are promotional pushes and new feature announcements.\n\n* * *\n\n### **Dependencies**\n\n1.  **External mediator confirmed in writing before the Grievance Channel opens:** This is the only hard gate in this project. No workaround. Dir. Student Services and Chief of Staff pursue this from T-6 weeks. If the mediator is a faculty member, Chief of Staff coordinates through the appropriate department chair. If it is OSA, Pauline initiates that relationship directly.\n    \n2.  **Moderation policy written and approved before the Suggestion Tab opens:** Dir. Student Services drafts it, Pauline approves it. It needs to exist as a document before the tab goes live so that any moderation decision made in the future has a written basis, not just a judgment call in the moment.\n    \n3.  **Student Rights Charter reviewed against the actual DLSU student handbook:** Chief of Staff and Dir. Student Services do this together. The charter cannot promise students rights that DLSU's own policies do not actually support. Anything that goes beyond existing policy needs to be framed as an advocacy position, not a guarantee.\n    \n4.  **72-hour Ledger rule formalized in the Comms Protocol:** Dir. Finance cannot be the only person enforcing this. It needs to be a written internal rule so that if Dir. Finance is unavailable, the Chief of Operations or Chief of Staff can post in their place without waiting for permission.\n    \n5.  **P&M clearance before any public announcement:** Dir. Creatives batches all four sub-features in one submission at T-2 weeks to avoid a staggered rollout that makes the platform look incomplete.\n    \n6.  **All platform features tested internally before launch:** Dir. Student Services runs a closed test of the Grievance Channel reply workflow and the Suggestion Tab notification system. If something breaks in testing, it gets fixed before students see it.","subprojects":"# Project 3: Transparency & Accountability Platform Sub-Projects\n\n## Centralized Grievance Channel\n\n*   **Description:** A private, secure way to report unfair grading or misconduct, with the council mediating directly and keeping every report confidential.\n\n## Financial Transparency Ledger\n\n*   **Description:** A public, regularly updated record of exactly where every peso of council funds goes.\n\n## Student Rights Charter\n\n*   **Description:** A clear, plain language guide to what every student can ask for, including grade breakdowns in any point of the term and the right to formally dispute a grade, among other things.\n\n## Suggestion Tab\n\n*   **Description:** A live, public space on the dashboard where any student can post an idea. The council reviews and replies to every single one, and if a student wants to head their own idea, we'll make room for it."},{"id":"project-4","folderName":"Project_4_Inclusion_Accessibility","name":"Project 4 Inclusion Accessibility","faq":"# Inclusion, Accessibility & Representation Initiative — FAQ\n\n**Q: Why should I trust this is actually free?** A: The Women and Minority in STEM Archive and the Laboratory Accessibility Audit require zero external funding. The FSL Training Program is fully funded by the council's internal operational budget to cover the honorarium for the professional instructors from our partner Deaf community organization. No fees are charged to students.\n\n**Q: What if someone submits fake achievements to the Women and Minority Archive?** A: The archive is strictly vetted. No profile or achievement is published without explicit, documented consent from the individual, along with verification of their academic standing or alumni status. We strictly comply with the Data Privacy Act (RA 10173).\n\n**Q: What happens if the administration completely ignores the Laboratory Accessibility Audit?** A: Our formal letter to the administration includes a strict 90-day response deadline. If the administration fails to provide a substantive response or a plan to fix the physical barriers we identify, the council will publish the full audit report publicly on the Transparency Platform to force accountability.\n\n**Q: Isn't an FSL program performative if our curriculum doesn't accommodate Deaf students anyway?** A: Systemic change has to start somewhere. Making our student leaders and peers conversational in FSL is the critical first step toward demonstrating demand and building the groundwork for broader, systemic curricular changes in the future. We cannot advocate for inclusion without practicing it ourselves.","description":"# Project Description\n\nThree actions built around one idea, that science spaces should actually work for the people inside them.","executionPlan":"## **Project 4: Inclusion, Accessibility & Representation Initiative**\n\n### **Execution Plan**\n\n**Classification note:** Mixed bucket. The Laboratory Accessibility Audit walkthrough and the FSL Training Program are Bucket A. The audit requires a formal Letter and Request (2-3 day lead time). The FSL Training Program requires a General Pre-Activity APS form (4-6 days), and a SLIFE form (5-8 days) since it is a Tie-Up Activity with an external organization, which routes through SLIFE, not APS alone. The Women and Minority in STEM Archive is Bucket B for ongoing operations, but its initial launch as a public-facing website qualifies as a Website/Social Media Launch under SLIFE (5-8 day lead time). Dir. Documentations files this before the first profile goes live.\n\nOne thing to flag upfront: the FSL Training Program cannot move forward until the External MOA with a Deaf community organization is signed. That MOA has a 14-day DAAM lead time on top of the time needed to actually negotiate it. This is the longest dependency in this project and it needs to start before anything else.\n\n* * *\n\n### **RACI Matrix**\n\n| Area | Responsible | Accountable | Consulted | Informed |\n| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |\n| FSL Training Program | Dir. Advocacy | President | Dir. EXT/INT, Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| FSL Partner MOA Negotiation | Dir. EXT/INT | President | Dir. Advocacy, Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| MOA DAAM Submission | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff | Dir. EXT/INT | President |\n| Laboratory Accessibility Audit | Dir. Advocacy | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| Audit Access Request Letter | Chief of Staff | President | Dir. Advocacy | Dir. Documentations |\n| Audit Report Writing | Dir. Advocacy | President | Chief of Staff | All Directors |\n| Audit Report Submission to Admin | President | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| 90-Day Response Tracking | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff | Dir. Advocacy | President |\n| Women and Minority in STEM Archive | Dir. Advocacy | President | Dir. Creatives | Dir. Documentations |\n| Consent Form for Archive | Dir. Advocacy | Chief of Staff |  | Dir. Documentations |\n| P\\&M for all public-facing items | Dir. Creatives | Chief Communications |  | Dir. Documentations |\n| APS and SLIFE Pre-Act Submissions | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff | Dir. Advocacy |  |\n| SLIFE Coordination (FSL) | Dir. EXT/INT | Chief Communications | Dir. Advocacy | Dir. Documentations |\n\n* * *\n\n### **Proposed Timeline**\n\n**T-10 Weeks (Before FSL Training Target Date)**\n\nDir. EXT/INT starts identifying and reaching out to Deaf community organizations in Metro Manila. The goal is to find a partner with formal FSL instruction capacity, not just a willing volunteer. Two or three options should be in conversation at once so that if one falls through, the MOA process does not start from scratch.\n\nDir. Advocacy reaches out to potential STEM Archive nominees at the same time. Graduating and recently shifted students do not stay reachable indefinitely. The earlier the consent forms go out, the better the response rate.\n\n**T-8 Weeks**\n\nA partner organization is selected. Dir. EXT/INT begins MOA negotiations with them in coordination with Dir. Advocacy. The MOA needs to cover at minimum: training frequency, number of sessions, scope of participants (students, faculty, or both), and who provides the trainer.\n\nChief of Staff drafts the formal access request letter for the Laboratory Accessibility Audit, addressed to the Dean's Office and Physical Facilities Management. Pauline signs it. The letter needs to include a proposed schedule for the walkthrough and a stated 90-day response deadline for the administration's action on the findings.\n\n**T-6 Weeks**\n\nMOA draft is finalized and submitted to DAAM. The 14-day external MOA lead time starts here. Dir. Documentations tracks the submission and flags any corrections immediately.\n\nDir. Advocacy sends the access request letter to the Dean's Office and PFM. The 90-day clock on the administration's response starts the moment it is delivered and acknowledged. Dir. Documentations logs the delivery date and sets a calendar reminder for the 90-day mark.\n\nDir. Advocacy also finalizes the consent form for the STEM Archive. It should cover: what information is shared, how it is displayed, how long it stays up, and how a graduate can request removal. Nothing goes on the archive without a signed form.\n\n**T-4 Weeks**\n\nMOA should be back from DAAM by now. If it comes back with corrections, Dir. EXT/INT and Dir. Documentations turn it around same day.\n\nDir. Documentations submits the APS Pre-Activity form for the FSL Training Program. If the partner organization qualifies as a social engagement or cross-org activity, the SLIFE form goes in at the same time (5-8 day lead time). Both go in together so they clear at roughly the same time.\n\nDir. Advocacy drafts the Lab Audit walkthrough schedule. The team doing the audit should include Dir. Advocacy, at least one faculty ally to facilitate access, and ideally one student with a disability who can speak directly to what barriers feel like in practice, not just what they look like on paper.\n\n**T-2 Weeks**\n\nPre-Acts and SLIFE form should be approved. If anything is still pending, Dir. Documentations escalates to Chief of Staff.\n\nDir. Creatives submits P&M clearance for the FSL Training Program announcement and the STEM Archive launch. Both can be submitted together.\n\nFirst batch of STEM Archive consent forms comes back. Dir. Advocacy reviews each one before any profile goes live. Consent is specific: if a graduate said yes to a photo but no to their thesis title being listed, that distinction is respected exactly.\n\n**FSL Training Program (Target: Weeks 2-4 of Term, Post-GOSM Defense)**\n\nSessions are scheduled based on the MOA terms. If the program covers both students and faculty, run separate sessions rather than mixing them, since faculty and students interact differently with material in a shared classroom setting. Dir. Advocacy coordinates attendance. Dir. Documentations files the AET feedback form within 7 days of each session.\n\n**Laboratory Accessibility Audit (Target: Week 2-3 of Term)**\n\nThe walkthrough happens once access is confirmed by the Dean's Office and PFM. Dir. Advocacy leads the team through every laboratory on the agreed list. Every barrier found is documented with a description, a photograph, and a note on which student population it affects. The report is not a suggestion. It is a formal submission to the Dean's Office and PFM with an explicit request for remediation and a reference to the 90-day response deadline already established in the original access request letter.\n\nIf the 90-day deadline passes with no response, Dir. Advocacy and Chief of Staff bring it to Pauline. The report goes public. This is not a threat held in reserve. It is a stated procedure written into the submission letter from the start.\n\n**Women and Minority in STEM Archive (Target: Week 1 of Term)**\n\nThe archive can go live as soon as the first batch of consented profiles is ready and P&M clears. It does not need to wait for a full roster. Starting with even five or six profiles is stronger than waiting three months for a complete list. Dir. Advocacy adds new profiles on a rolling basis throughout the term as more consent forms come in. Dir. Documentations submits the SLIFE pre-activity for the archive website launch before the first profile goes up. P&M follows after.\n\n**Blackout Compliance**\n\n*   FSL Training sessions should not be scheduled during Midterms (Feb 16-21) or ILW (Mar 2-7). If the program runs multiple sessions, schedule them in Weeks 2-5 and then again post-ILW.\n*   The Lab Audit walkthrough is not a student activity in the DAAM sense, but scheduling it during Midterms creates unnecessary friction. Target Week 2-3.\n*   Archive updates are a standing platform feature and continue through all blackout windows without issue.\n*   MOA submission at T-6 weeks should fall in early January, well before any blackout periods.\n\n* * *\n\n### **Dependencies**\n\n1.  **FSL partner MOA signed and DAAM-cleared before any FSL session is announced publicly:** Dir. EXT/INT starts this at T-10 weeks. The program does not get promoted until the MOA clears. A named partner organization in the promotion is more credible and more defensible than a vague announcement.\n    \n2.  **Dean's Office and PFM access confirmation before the Lab Audit walkthrough:** The letter goes out at T-6 weeks. If access is denied, Chief of Staff escalates to Pauline and the two of them pursue it directly at the administrative level. The audit does not get cancelled because of an unresponsive office. It gets delayed until access is granted, and that delay is documented.\n    \n3.  **Faculty ally confirmed for the audit team:** Dir. Advocacy identifies this person before the walkthrough is scheduled. A faculty presence makes the visit harder for building management to dismiss or delay.\n    \n4.  **Consent forms returned and reviewed before any profile goes live on the STEM Archive:** Dir. Advocacy owns this review. No profile goes up without explicit written consent, no matter how public the person's achievements already are.\n    \n5.  **APS and SLIFE Pre-Acts cleared before FSL program promotion goes public:** Dir. Documentations submits both at T-4 weeks. Dir. Creatives holds all event-specific P&M until both come back approved.\n    \n6.  **90-day response deadline documented from day of audit report delivery:** Dir. Documentations logs the exact delivery date. Chief of Staff sets a calendar alert. This date is not approximate. The 90-day follow-up procedure is triggered on that exact day if no substantive response has come.","subprojects":"# Project 4: Inclusion, Accessibility & Representation Initiative Sub-Projects\n\n## Filipino Sign Language Training Program\n\n*   **Description:** Formal FSL training for students and faculty, so the Deaf and hard of hearing community isn't an afterthought in our classrooms and labs.\n\n## Laboratory Accessibility Audit\n\n*   **Description:** A real, student led review of every laboratory to find physical barriers for students with disabilities, with a formal report submitted to the administration for fixing.\n\n## Women and Minority in STEM\n\n*   **Description:** A public record and posting of the academic and professional achievements of women and minority graduates in this college, so current students have proof, not just encouragement, that they belong here."},{"id":"project-5","folderName":"Project_5_Queer_Trans_Education","name":"Project 5 Queer Trans Education","faq":"# Queer & Trans Identity Education Series — FAQ\n\n**Q: Why should I trust this is actually free?** A: The educational forums require minimal funding, strictly for tokens of appreciation for our academic speakers, which is covered by the existing council budget. The Shanghay Laya website is built with open-source tools. No fees are charged to students for any part of this initiative.\n\n**Q: What if the Shanghay Laya website provides dangerous medical advice?** A: Shanghay Laya is explicitly a directory, not a medical provider. It features a legally reviewed disclaimer stating this fact. The hormone-resource section strictly links _only_ to licensed endocrinologists and established clinics. We completely prohibit links to informal sources or DIY hormone guides to ensure complete safety and legality.\n\n**Q: What if the administration tries to censor the Science Forum or block the event?** A: The forum is strictly grounded in peer-reviewed biological and sociological science, led by credentialed academics. If the administration attempts to block rigorous academic discourse, we will leverage our faculty partners and the Student Rights Charter to defend our fundamental right to academic freedom.\n\n**Q: Why is the council wasting time on a \"niche minority issue\" instead of things that affect everyone?** A: Science is objective, yet queer and trans students face unscientific prejudice every day in our classrooms. Clarifying the science behind our own identities isn't a niche issue; it's a defense of our community's right to exist safely and unapologetically on campus. Inclusivity affects the integrity of the entire college.","description":"# Project Description\n\nThree sessions, one grounded in current science and one grounded in Philippine history, built to make one point clearly: queer and trans Filipinos have always been part of this community.","executionPlan":"## **Project 5: Queer & Trans Identity Education Series**\n\n### **Execution Plan**\n\n**Classification note:** Mixed bucket. The Queer Identity Science Forum and the Pre-Colonial Gender & Trans History Session are both Bucket A, each requiring a General Pre-Activity APS form (4-6 day lead time). Given that all speakers must hold academic positions or peer-reviewed credentials per this plan's own standard, both sessions will almost certainly qualify as Seminars/Workshops with Distinguished Speakers, routing through SLIFE (5-8 days). Plan for this as a certainty. Confirm with DAAM before assuming APS alone covers it. Shanghay Laya is Bucket B for ongoing operations, but the site launch is a Website/Social Media Launch that routes through SLIFE (5-8 day lead time). Dir. Documentations files the SLIFE pre-activity alongside the legal disclaimer review, not after it. However, Shanghay Laya carries a legal dependency that no other Bucket B feature in this platform has: a legally reviewed disclaimer must be in place before the site goes live. That review is a hard gate, not a suggestion.\n\n* * *\n\n### **RACI Matrix**\n\n| Area | Responsible | Accountable | Consulted | Informed |\n| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |\n| Queer Identity Science Forum | Dir. Advocacy | President | Chief of Staff, Dir. National Affairs | Dir. Documentations |\n| Pre-Colonial Gender & Trans History Session | Dir. Advocacy | President | Dir. National Affairs, Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| Speaker Identification & Vetting | Dir. Advocacy | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| SLIFE Coordination (External Speakers) | Dir. EXT/INT | Chief Communications | Dir. Advocacy | Dir. Documentations |\n| APS and SLIFE Pre-Act Submissions | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff | Dir. Advocacy |  |\n| Shanghay Laya Website | Dir. Advocacy | President | Dir. Creatives, Chief Communications | Dir. Documentations |\n| Legal Disclaimer Review | Chief of Staff | President | Dir. Advocacy | Dir. Documentations |\n| Hormone Resource Vetting | Dir. Advocacy | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| P\\&M for all public-facing items | Dir. Creatives | Chief Communications | Dir. Advocacy | Dir. Documentations |\n| Venue Booking (both sessions) | Dir. Logistics | Chief of Operations | Dir. Advocacy | Dir. Documentations |\n| Post-Activity Report (both sessions) | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff | Dir. Advocacy |  |\n\n* * *\n\n### **Proposed Timeline**\n\n**T-10 Weeks (Before Target Session Dates)**\n\nSpeaker identification starts here, and the standard is non-negotiable from day one. Every speaker for both sessions must hold a relevant academic position or have published peer-reviewed research in their field. Dir. Advocacy draws up a shortlist of at minimum three candidates per session so that if one declines or becomes unavailable, the program does not stall.\n\nFor the Science Forum, the search covers researchers in biology, psychology, or sociology with published work on queer identities. For the History Session, the search focuses on Philippine historians or anthropologists with documented work on pre-colonial gender diversity or the Babaylan tradition specifically.\n\nDir. Advocacy also starts building the Shanghay Laya content list at this point, identifying which organizations, clinics, and resources will be linked. Every hormone resource entry gets flagged for the legal disclaimer review before the site goes live.\n\n**T-8 Weeks**\n\nSpeaker confirmations are targeted by this point. Dir. Advocacy secures written confirmation from each speaker, covering session date, format, and scope of presentation. If either speaker is external to DLSU, Dir. EXT/INT begins the SLIFE coordination process immediately since the 5-8 day lead time only counts from submission, not from when the decision to invite was made.\n\nChief of Staff begins the legal disclaimer review for Shanghay Laya. This does not require a licensed lawyer. A law student with sufficient background, reviewed carefully, is enough. What the review needs to confirm: the website is a directory, not a medical provider; every hormone resource link goes to a licensed endocrinologist or LGBTQ+-affirming clinic; and the disclaimer on every page is specific enough to be defensible, not just a generic \"consult your doctor\" line. The review is documented, signed off, and filed with Dir. Documentations before the site goes live.\n\n**T-6 Weeks**\n\nDir. Documentations submits APS Pre-Activity forms for both sessions. If external speakers are confirmed, SLIFE forms go in at the same time. Both sessions can be submitted together since they are part of the same project.\n\nDir. Logistics books venues for both sessions. The Science Forum and the History Session are separate events and do not need to happen on the same day, but scheduling them within the same two-week window keeps the project cohesive and the promotional momentum from the first session carries into the second.\n\nDir. Advocacy finalizes all Shanghay Laya content. Every link is checked. Anything that cannot be verified as a licensed or peer-reviewed source does not make it onto the site. The hormone resources section specifically lists only licensed endocrinologists and LGBTQ+-affirming clinics, with each entry reviewed individually by Dir. Advocacy before inclusion.\n\n**T-4 Weeks**\n\nPre-Act approvals should be back. If anything is rejected or comes back with corrections, Dir. Documentations flags it to Chief of Staff same day and resubmits.\n\nLegal disclaimer review for Shanghay Laya is completed and signed off. Dir. Advocacy and Chief of Staff both sign the confirmation that the review happened and who conducted it. This document lives in Dir. Documentations' clearance tracker permanently.\n\nDir. Creatives submits P&M clearance for both session announcements. Dir. Documentations submits the SLIFE pre-activity for the Shanghay Laya website launch (5-8 day lead time) at the same time. Both go in together but they are separate submissions going to separate channels.\n\n**T-2 Weeks**\n\nPromotion for both sessions goes live once P&M clears. Dir. Creatives leads the rollout across platforms. Promotional materials for the sessions name the speakers and their credentials. This is not just good marketing. It is the first line of defense against any challenge to the academic legitimacy of the content.\n\nShanghay Laya goes live at this point if the legal disclaimer review is complete and P&M has cleared. It does not wait for the sessions. The website is a standing resource and students may need it before either event happens.\n\n**Session Week (Target: Weeks 3-5 of Term, Post-GOSM Defense)**\n\nThe two sessions are scheduled within a two-week window of each other. The Science Forum runs first since it grounds the academic basis for queer and trans identities. The History Session follows, building on that foundation with pre-colonial context. Running them in this order is intentional: science first, history second, so the narrative arc is clear.\n\nDir. Advocacy manages the room for both sessions. Dir. Documentations has an AET feedback form ready for distribution at the end of each session. Forms are collected before people leave, not sent digitally afterward where response rates drop significantly.\n\nDir. Documentations submits Post-Activity reports for both sessions within 5 days of each event.\n\n**Blackout Compliance**\n\nBoth sessions target Weeks 3-5 of the term. This clears GOSM Defense (Jan 19-24) and lands well before Midterms (Feb 16-21). No sessions are scheduled during Midterms, ILW (Mar 2-7), or the Activity Ban (Mar 30 - Apr 11). Shanghay Laya as a standing platform is unaffected by all blackout windows. Promotion pauses during ILW and Midterms but the site stays live.\n\n* * *\n\n### **Dependencies**\n\n1.  **Speaker credentials confirmed in writing before any promotion goes out:** Dir. Advocacy owns this. A speaker's name appears in promotional materials only after their academic position or published research has been verified and documented. No exceptions, regardless of how trusted or well-known the person is within the community.\n    \n2.  **Legal disclaimer review completed and signed off before Shanghay Laya goes live:** Chief of Staff coordinates this. The site does not open without it. If the review is still pending when everything else is ready, the site launch moves, not the review deadline.\n    \n3.  **All hormone resource links verified as licensed providers before site launch:** Dir. Advocacy reviews each entry individually. This is not a task that gets delegated to a committee or done as a batch check. Every link is opened, the provider's license or institutional affiliation is confirmed, and the link is logged in a master list that Dir. Documentations keeps on file.\n    \n4.  **APS Pre-Acts and SLIFE forms cleared before event-specific promotion goes live:** Dir. Documentations submits both at T-6 weeks. P&M clearance for general awareness posts can happen earlier, but date-specific promotional materials wait for Pre-Act approval.\n    \n5.  **Venue secured before session dates are announced publicly:** Dir. Logistics confirms both venues before any date appears in promotional materials. Announcing a date and then changing it because a room fell through undermines the credibility of the whole initiative.\n    \n6.  **AET feedback forms collected in person at the end of each session:** Dir. Documentations prepares physical forms for both events. Digital follow-up is a backup, not the primary collection method.","subprojects":"# Project 5: Queer & Trans Identity Education Series Sub-Projects\n\n## Queer Identity Science Forum\n\n*   **Description:** An academic session on the biological, psychological, and sociological research behind queer identities, taught plainly and without apology.\n\n## Pre-Colonial Gender & Trans History\n\n*   **Description:** A look at gender diversity in pre-colonial Philippine history, including the Babaylan, so students understand this isn't a new conversation, it's a returning one.\n\n## Shanghay Laya–Malaya Maging Ikaw, Sa Gitna ng Lahat\n\n*   **Description:** A website that includes anything queer, trans, medical research, myths debunked, sources for hormones, therapy, and trusted news sites."},{"id":"project-6","folderName":"Project_6_Emergency_Response","name":"Project 6 Emergency Response","faq":"# Student Emergency Response & Relief Program — FAQ\n\n**Q: Why isn't the pantry logging names to prevent hoarding?** A: Food insecurity is heavily stigmatized. A \"no questions asked\" policy is necessary to ensure those who genuinely need it aren't too ashamed to use it. We monitor for abuse by tracking inventory outflow anomalies (logging item types and quantities taken) rather than policing individual students.\n\n**Q: Who decides when we escalate to a Tier 3 calamity?** A: It is strictly objective. Tier 3 is triggered automatically by an official PAGASA Signal No. 2+ bulletin or a formal LGU Calamity Declaration. It is not based on council members' subjective opinions or internal debate.\n\n**Q: Where do the exact peso figures for the Emergency Fund come from?** A: They are realistic caps derived directly from our sustainable organizational budget. By capping Tier 1 at ₱500 and pivoting to flat-pool allocations during Tier 4, we ensure the fund can assist students across the entire academic year without going bankrupt during the first major typhoon.\n\n**Q: What happens to my data in the Welfare Outreach Registry?** A: The registry is strictly opt-in and RA 10173-compliant. Your data is accessible only to elected officers for emergency outreach, and it is automatically and permanently deleted at the end of the academic term unless you explicitly re-consent for the next term. We do not hold onto your private data indefinitely.","description":"# Project Description\n\nThe part of this platform built for survival, not convenience.","executionPlan":"## **Project 6: Student Emergency Response & Relief Program**\n\n### **Execution Plan**\n\n**Classification note:** Mixed bucket. The Food Security Pantry and Emergency Micro-Grant Fund are both Bucket B, but both require a Special Approval Slip on top of P&M clearance before any funds move. The Welfare Outreach Registry is Bucket B for ongoing operations, but its public launch is a Website/Social Media Launch and routes through SLIFE (5-8 day lead time) before going live. Confirm with DAAM whether the registry, which collects sensitive vulnerability data from students, qualifies as Survey Dissemination with Sensitive Information (SLIFE) rather than just a Website/Social Media Launch. File whichever category applies. The financial mechanics here are more complex than any other project in this platform. A dedicated feasibility analysis has been completed and is referenced throughout this plan. Every financial step below is grounded in that document and the 16th USG Treasurer's Manual.\n\n**One thing to flag before anything else:** two administrative requirements must be completed before any financial transaction in this project can legally happen. Specimen signatures submitted to OTREAS, and the Treasurer's Exam passed by Dir. Finance. OTREAS freezes the account without both. These are not bureaucratic formalities to handle eventually. They are the first two items on the pre-launch checklist.\n\n* * *\n\n### **RACI Matrix**\n\n| Area | Responsible | Accountable | Consulted | Informed |\n| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |\n| Pantry Operations | Dir. Logistics | Chief of Operations | Dir. Finance | Dir. Documentations |\n| Pantry Initial Stock Purchase (Direct Payment, Procurement) | Dir. Finance | Chief of Operations | Dir. Logistics | President |\n| Pantry Restock Trigger | Dir. Logistics | Chief of Operations | Dir. Finance | Dir. Documentations |\n| Emergency Micro-Grant Fund Operations | Dir. Student Services | President | Dir. Finance | Dir. Documentations |\n| DF Ring-Fence Declaration in GOSM | Dir. Finance | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| Officer Advance Protocol (Written Memo) | President | President | Dir. Finance | Chief of Staff |\n| Micro-Grant Disbursement Processing (Direct Payment) | Dir. Finance | President | Dir. Student Services | Dir. Documentations |\n| Batch Disbursement LOE Preparation | Dir. Finance | Chief of Operations | Dir. Student Services | President |\n| Calamity Tier Activation Decision | President | President | Chief of Operations | All Directors |\n| Welfare Outreach Registry | Dir. Student Services | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| Specimen Signature Submission to OTREAS | Dir. Finance | President |  | Dir. Documentations |\n| Treasurer's Exam | Dir. Finance | President |  | Chief of Staff |\n| FRA Report After Semana ng Siyensya | Dir. Finance | Chief of Operations | Dir. Documentations | President |\n| Transparency Ledger Updates | Dir. Finance | Chief of Operations |  | Dir. Documentations |\n| P\\&M Clearance for all sub-features | Dir. Creatives | Chief Communications |  | Dir. Documentations |\n| All formal submissions and tracking | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff | Dir. Finance |  |\n\n* * *\n\n### **Proposed Timeline**\n\nThe timeline for this project runs in two phases. Phase 1 is all pre-launch financial architecture. Phase 2 is operations. Getting Phase 1 wrong means the pantry has no goods on its first day, the micro-grant fund cannot process a single disbursement, and OTREAS can freeze the account entirely. Phase 1 is the work most councils skip. We do not skip it.\n\n**T-8 Weeks (Before Term Start)**\n\nDir. Finance submits specimen signatures to OTREAS and schedules the Treasurer's Exam. Both done in the same week. Neither can be left for later because every financial transaction in this project, from pantry stock to micro-grant disbursements, requires OTREAS account access.\n\nDir. Finance also drafts the DF ring-fence declaration for inclusion in the GOSM submission. The declaration establishes a non-negotiable internal floor on the Depository Fund. The language is specific: the Emergency Micro-Grant DF allocation for the academic year is declared, and the carry-over minimum plus a buffer is marked permanently untouchable. Disbursements may only draw from income generated above that floor. This is not an informal agreement. It goes into the GOSM in writing.\n\nPauline and Dir. Finance draft and sign the Officer Advance Protocol memo at the same time. This is the internal policy that makes Tier 1 emergencies possible within 24-48 hours. The memo establishes that Pauline or an authorized officer may advance cash from personal funds for true same-day emergencies, and that a formal reimbursement through Direct Payment Student is filed immediately afterward. The student is never the one waiting. The officer floats it and gets reimbursed within 21 days through the formal channel.\n\n**T-6 Weeks**\n\nTreasurer's Exam should be cleared by this point. Dir. Finance confirms account access with OTREAS before filing anything else.\n\nDir. Finance files the initial Pantry stock purchase as a Direct Payment (Procurement) transaction. This is the most time-sensitive single action in the entire pre-launch phase. The 21-day processing lead time means if this is filed at T-6 weeks, goods arrive approximately at T-3 weeks, which is exactly when you want a full shelf ready before the term even starts. The document chain for this transaction: PRS Table, Direct Payment Memo, List of Expenses, Official Receipt, Approved A-Form, and Proof of Approval.\n\nThe pantry seed budget is declared as a programmatic line within the Operational Fund using GL Code 512201001 (Food and Meals) for rice and canned goods, and GL Code 511001004 (Other Materials and Supplies) for storage containers and inventory tracking materials. The Pantry runs on the Operational Fund, not the Depository Fund. This distinction matters because the Operational Fund has no carry-over minimum requirement. It is a use-it-or-lose-it annual allocation, which means spending it on the pantry is exactly what it is designed for.\n\nDir. Student Services sets up the Welfare Outreach Registry intake form. The form collects name, contact number, and self-declared vulnerability status. Data privacy notice goes on the form before it is shared with anyone. Dir. Documentations files P&M clearance for the registry.\n\n**T-4 Weeks**\n\nDF ring-fence declaration confirmed in the GOSM submission. Dir. Finance cross-checks that the declared floor accounts for the carry-over minimum plus a buffer before any projected disbursements are committed.\n\nDir. Creatives submits P&M clearance for the Pantry launch and the Emergency Micro-Grant Fund. The SCT for both fund-disbursing features goes in at the same time (1-3 day processing). Dir. Documentations tracks both submissions.\n\nDir. Student Services finalizes the micro-grant intake process: what information a student submits, who reviews it, and what the turnaround commitment is. For Tier 1 emergencies, the Officer Advance Protocol activates and the student is helped within 24-48 hours. For Tier 2 and above, the formal Direct Payment channel is used with the 21-day lead time accepted because calamity triggers give advance warning.\n\n**T-2 Weeks**\n\nPantry stock should be arriving or confirmed for delivery based on the T-6 procurement filing. Dir. Logistics confirms inventory and sets up the storage system. The restock trigger rule is formalized: when stock drops to 20% remaining, Dir. Logistics flags Dir. Finance and a new Direct Payment (Procurement) is filed the same day. The 21-day clock on restocking starts the moment that flag is raised, not when stock runs out.\n\nAll P&M clearances and SCT approvals should be back. Dir. Documentations confirms all clearances are logged before launch.\n\n**Term Start: Both Features Go Live**\n\nThe Pantry opens fully stocked on Day 1. No questions asked. Dir. Logistics manages the daily inventory log, tracking item types and quantities per visit without recording student names. This is how the no-questions-asked policy and the usage data coexist. We know what is being taken, not who is taking it.\n\nThe Emergency Micro-Grant Fund is operational from Day 1 with the Officer Advance Protocol in place for same-day emergencies. Dir. Student Services is the first contact for any student seeking a grant. The process from there depends on the tier.\n\n**Calamity Tier Framework**\n\nThis is the operational heart of the project. Every person in the council should know which tier is active before making any disbursement decision.\n\nTier\n\nTrigger\n\nDisbursement Method\n\nTurnaround\n\nTier 1 (Individual)\n\nPersonal emergency, no declared calamity\n\nOfficer Advance, formal reimbursement filed immediately after\n\n24-48 hours\n\nTier 2 (Localized)\n\nDLSU-only class suspension\n\n2-officer approval, formal Direct Payment filed\n\nSame day filing, 21-day processing\n\nTier 3 (Declared Calamity)\n\nPAGASA Signal No. 2+ or LGU/national calamity declaration\n\nEmergency process: batch Credit Memo pre-processed for Welfare Registry priority list\n\nPre-filed during approach, disbursed when approved\n\nTier 4 (Widespread Disaster)\n\nMulti-day suspension, large-scale student impact\n\nPooled flat aid per affected student prioritized from Welfare Registry, batched into single LOE\n\nPre-filed proactively\n\nThe trigger source for Tier 3 and 4 is always external and official. PAGASA bulletin or a formal DLSU or LGU announcement. No internal council vote determines whether a calamity is real. The official declaration determines it.\n\n**Batching is standard practice for Tier 1 disbursements.** Instead of filing a separate Direct Payment for every individual ₱500 grant, Dir. Finance batches all Tier 1 grants from the same week into one Letter of Explanation and one transaction. This keeps the admin load manageable and satisfies OTREAS requirements without creating 10 separate paperwork packets for 10 students in the same week.\n\n**Post-Semana ng Siyensya (After P2 Merch Closes)**\n\nOnce Semana ng Siyensya concludes and FAO has processed all receipts, Dir. Finance compiles the FRA Report. Net profit above ₱5,000 triggers a full Fundraising Activity Report: Income Statement, approved deposit slip from OTREAS, screenshot of OTREAS email acknowledgment, and compiled confirmation receipts in one PDF. This must be filed within one week of the activity's conclusion.\n\nThe public Transparency Ledger update showing the proceeds split happens after FAO confirms all receipts are processed. Not 48 hours after the event. After FAO confirmation. The feasibility analysis is explicit on this and it is the correct sequence.\n\n100% of Semana ng Siyensya merch net proceeds transfer into the DF Emergency Micro-Grant ring-fenced allocation.\n\nThe same FRA Report protocol applies to the Fundraising and Local Business Initiative (P8), with 70% of net proceeds routing to the Emergency Fund DF and 30% to the Research Grants Pool.\n\n**Ongoing Pantry Restock**\n\nEvery restock follows the same paperwork chain: Dir. Logistics raises the flag at 20%, Dir. Finance files the Direct Payment (Procurement) same day, 21-day clock starts. Since the Pantry opened fully stocked, there is always a buffer. The clock never starts at zero.\n\n**Blackout Compliance**\n\nThe Pantry and Emergency Fund run through all blackout windows without interruption. They are not activities. Midterms (Feb 16-21), ILW (Mar 2-7), and the Activity Ban (Mar 30 - Apr 11) do not pause operations. If anything, calamity season and student stress peaks around exam periods, which is exactly when the Tier 1 officer advance mechanism needs to be the most ready.\n\n* * *\n\n### **Dependencies**\n\n1.  **Specimen signatures at OTREAS and Treasurer's Exam cleared before any transaction is filed:** Dir. Finance handles both at T-8 weeks. No financial transaction in this project can move without account access. This is the first thing done, not the last.\n    \n2.  **DF ring-fence floor declared in the GOSM before the fund accepts any income or makes any disbursement:** The floor is not set informally. It is in the GOSM in writing, and it is set before Semana ng Siyensya merch proceeds arrive. You cannot retroactively protect a floor after you have already started spending.\n    \n3.  **Pantry initial stock Direct Payment filed at T-6 weeks:** The 21-day procurement lead time makes this non-negotiable. Filing late means the pantry opens with an empty shelf. The pro move from the feasibility analysis applies here: stock generously at launch so the 21-day restock clock never starts from a crisis.\n    \n4.  **Officer Advance Protocol signed by Pauline and Dir. Finance before term starts:** The protocol exists as a written internal document. If a Tier 1 emergency happens on Day 1 of term and there is no signed protocol, there is no legal basis for the advance mechanism. It must exist before it is needed.\n    \n5.  **Restock trigger formalized at 20% inventory:** Dir. Logistics and Dir. Finance agree on this in writing before the pantry opens, not after the first restock is needed. The trigger is a signal, not a judgment call.\n    \n6.  **FRA Report filed within one week of Semana ng Siyensya conclusion, after FAO confirmation:** Dir. Finance leads this. Dir. Documentations compiles all deposit slips and receipts into one PDF. The Transparency Ledger update goes out after this is confirmed, not before.\n    \n7.  **Welfare Registry data compliance verified before the form goes public:** Dir. Student Services confirms the intake form carries the data privacy notice, that data is accessible only to elected officers, and that the term-end data wipe is built into the process from the start, not added as an afterthought.\n    \n8.  **Batching protocol established before the first disbursement is filed:** Dir. Finance and Dir. Student Services agree on the weekly batching schedule before the term starts. Same-week Tier 1 grants go into one LOE, one transaction. This is a standing procedure, not a case-by-case decision.\n    \n9.  **Direct Payment Student Reimbursement availability confirmed:** Dir. Finance confirms with OTREAS before term starts whether the Direct Payment (Student) Reimbursement is still available in the current term. The Treasurer's Manual flags it as a Term 1-only transaction. If it has been removed, Dir. Finance identifies the alternative reimbursement pathway with OTREAS and updates the Officer Advance Protocol accordingly before it is signed.","subprojects":"# Project 6: Student Emergency Response & Relief Program Sub-Projects\n\n## Food Security Pantry\n\n*   **Description:** No questions asked: access to rice, canned goods, and other essentials for any student facing hunger.\n\n## Emergency Micro-Grant Fund\n\n*   **Description:** Fast, small disbursements for students who suddenly cannot afford commute fare, medicine, or other urgent needs.\n\n## Welfare Outreach Registry\n\n*   **Description:** A registry students can opt into themselves to receive priority outreach during emergencies or disasters. All data is self-reported, never collected without consent, and handled only by elected council officers under strict confidentiality. Nothing is shared, sold, or kept longer than needed."},{"id":"project-7","folderName":"Project_7_Financial_Empowerment","name":"Project 7 Financial Empowerment","faq":"# Student Financial Empowerment Initiative — FAQ\n\n**Q: What if the lab equipment or calculator I got from the Exchange doesn't work perfectly?** A: All items on the Equipment & Apparel Exchange are entirely donation-based and come with **no implied warranty**. While our team conducts a basic condition check and labels items as \"Tested\" or \"Untested\", students claim items at their own risk and discretion.\n\n**Q: I have work during the Freelancing Seminar. How can I get the tips?** A: We know working students have the tightest schedules. That is why we explicitly planned to record the live seminar. The full recording and presentation slides will be permanently archived and available on the Student Resource Hub within 48 hours after the event concludes.\n\n**Q: Is the Student Council partnered with or endorsing the freelancing platforms mentioned in the seminar?** A: No. Pauline will be sharing her personal, lived experience as a working student who funds her own degree. The council does not officially endorse, sponsor, or partner with any specific freelancing company, agency, or platform mentioned during her talk.","description":"# Project Description\n\nTwo ways to ease financial pressure without asking anyone for money they don't have.","executionPlan":"## **Project 7: Student Financial Empowerment Initiative**\n\n### **Execution Plan**\n\n**Classification note:** Mixed bucket. The Equipment and Apparel Exchange is Bucket B for ongoing operations, but the platform launch is a Website/Social Media Launch that routes through SLIFE (5-8 day lead time) before going public. Dir. Documentations files this at the same time as the donation drive pre-launch so both clear before the site opens. The pre-launch donation drive is a Donation Drive under SLIFE (5-8 day lead time). Dir. Documentations files this at the same time as the website launch SLIFE so both clear before anything goes public. The Freelancing and Part-Time Work Seminar is Bucket A, requiring a General Pre-Activity APS form (4-6 days). The seminar is a Career Related project, which routes through OCCS under SLIFE (5-8 day lead time). File the OCCS SLIFE form — do not assume APS alone is sufficient. Dir. Documentations confirms this with DAAM before filing. Both sub-projects are zero-cost. No SCT, no DF involvement, no fundraising compliance requirements.\n\nTwo things define this project before the timeline even starts. First, the Equipment Exchange needs donations before it has anything to offer. A platform with zero listings on launch day is functionally useless. The donation drive starts before the exchange goes live, not after. Second, Pauline is the primary speaker for the Freelancing Seminar. She is speaking from her own experience as a working student. The seminar carries a clear disclaimer, verbal and on screen, that nothing said constitutes an endorsement of any specific platform or company. This distinction is non-negotiable and it gets communicated in the promotion, not just at the event.\n\n* * *\n\n### **RACI Matrix**\n\n| Area | Responsible | Accountable | Consulted | Informed |\n| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |\n| Equipment & Apparel Exchange (Platform) | Dir. Student Services | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| Donation Drive (Pre-Launch) | Dir. EXT/INT | Chief of Operations | Dir. Student Services | Dir. Documentations |\n| Item Condition Check System | Dir. Student Services | Chief of Staff | Dir. Logistics | Dir. Documentations |\n| Exchange Platform Listing Management | Dir. Student Services | President |  | Dir. Documentations |\n| Freelancing Seminar (Overall) | Dir. Student Services | President | Chief Communications | Dir. Documentations |\n| Seminar Speaker Preparation (Pauline) | President | President | Chief Communications | Dir. Student Services |\n| APS Pre-Act Submission | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff | Dir. Student Services |  |\n| SLIFE Coordination (OCCS, if required) | Dir. EXT/INT | Chief Communications | Dir. Student Services | Dir. Documentations |\n| Venue Booking (Seminar) | Dir. Logistics | Chief of Operations | Dir. Student Services | Dir. Documentations |\n| Recording Setup (Seminar) | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff | Dir. Creatives | Dir. Logistics |\n| Archive Upload to Hub (within 48 hours) | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff | Dir. Academics |  |\n| Disclaimer (verbal \\+ on screen) | President | President | Chief Communications | Dir. Creatives |\n| P\\&M for all public-facing items | Dir. Creatives | Chief Communications | Dir. Student Services | Dir. Documentations |\n| All clearance tracking | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff |  |  |\n\n* * *\n\n### **Proposed Timeline**\n\n**T-8 Weeks (Before Term Start)**\n\nDir. EXT/INT launches the pre-launch donation drive. This is targeted at graduating students and those who have recently shifted out of COS programs. The pitch is straightforward: lab gowns, scientific calculators, and tools that served you well should serve someone else next. The drive runs through org communication channels, batch group chats, and coordination with department student organizations to reach the most likely donors. Dir. Documentations submits the SLIFE pre-activity for the donation drive alongside the general outreach plan. 5-8 day lead time.\n\nDir. Student Services drafts the item condition check protocol at the same time. Every donated item goes through a basic assessment before it is listed: tested or untested, functional or not, and condition noted clearly. Every listing carries a visible no-implied-warranty disclaimer. The exchange is donation-based. Students receiving items understand this from the start.\n\nDir. Documentations confirms with DAAM whether the Freelancing Seminar requires a SLIFE form through OCCS in addition to the standard APS. Career-related activities sometimes fall under OCCS jurisdiction. Knowing this at T-8 weeks gives enough time to file both forms at the correct lead times without rushing.\n\n**T-6 Weeks**\n\nFirst batch of donated items has come in from the drive. Dir. Student Services runs the condition checks and starts building the initial listing inventory. A platform with ten to fifteen verified, listed items at launch is enough to prove the concept. It does not need to be exhaustive on day one.\n\nDir. Documentations files the APS Pre-Activity form for the Freelancing Seminar. If the OCCS SLIFE is required, it goes in the same week. Both forms should clear well before the target seminar date.\n\nDir. Logistics books the venue for the seminar. Physical venue is preferred over a fully online session since the dynamic between Pauline and the audience is part of what makes this seminar worth attending. A hybrid option can be set up for students who cannot attend in person, but the primary session is live.\n\nDir. Creatives starts developing the P&M materials for both sub-projects. The Equipment Exchange promotion emphasizes the donation ask as much as the recipient benefit. Both sides of the exchange need awareness to function.\n\n**T-4 Weeks**\n\nPre-Act approvals should be back by this point. If the SLIFE is still pending, Dir. Documentations flags Chief of Staff immediately.\n\nDir. Creatives submits P&M clearance for the Equipment Exchange platform launch and for the Freelancing Seminar announcement. These can go in together.\n\nRecording setup for the seminar is confirmed. Dir. Documentations owns this specifically. The recording equipment or setup is tested before the event, not on the day of. The 48-hour archive upload window starts the moment the seminar ends, so there is no room for technical issues discovered after the fact.\n\nPauline finalizes the seminar structure with Chief Communications. The session covers freelancing platforms, setting rates, managing client relationships, balancing workload with academic requirements, and legitimate part-time options beyond call center and food service work. The flow is conversational, not a deck-heavy presentation. Pauline speaks from what she has actually done, and that framing is established early in the session alongside the explicit no-endorsement disclaimer.\n\n**T-2 Weeks**\n\nEquipment Exchange platform is ready. Listings are live in draft, pending P&M clearance before going public. Dir. Student Services does a final walkthrough of the condition check labels and disclaimer text on each listing.\n\nDonation drive has its final push. Dir. EXT/INT coordinates one last call to graduating students before the exchange goes live.\n\nSeminar promotion goes out once P&M clears. The promotional materials name Pauline as the speaker and frame it accurately: a session on working through college, drawn from real experience. No platform names appear in the promotional materials.\n\n**Week 1-2 of Term: Equipment Exchange Goes Live**\n\nPlatform launches with the initial batch of listed items. The donation channel stays open throughout the term. Dir. Student Services manages incoming donations on a rolling basis, running each item through the condition check before listing. The exchange is not a one-time event. It is a permanent standing feature of the Hub.\n\n**Week 3-4 of Term: Freelancing and Part-Time Work Seminar**\n\nThis window clears GOSM Defense (Jan 19-24) and keeps reasonable distance from Midterms (Feb 16-21). The seminar runs live, hybrid format, with Dir. Documentations managing the recording from start to finish.\n\nAt the opening of the session, Pauline states the disclaimer clearly and on the projected screen behind her: this session reflects personal experience and does not constitute an endorsement of any platform, company, or employer. The disclaimer is not buried in fine print. It is said out loud at the start.\n\nDir. Documentations files the AET feedback form immediately after the session. Feedback forms are collected in person before attendees leave.\n\nWithin 48 hours of the seminar, Dir. Documentations uploads the full recording to the Student Resource Hub on Project 1. This is not optional and it does not extend to 72 hours. The archive is the reason the seminar was recorded. Students who could not attend, and students in future terms, need access to it. Dir. Academics confirms the upload is live on the Hub and accessible.\n\nDir. Documentations files the Post-Activity report within 5 days of the seminar.\n\n**Blackout Compliance**\n\nThe Equipment Exchange is a standing platform feature and runs through all blackout windows without interruption. Donations continue, listings continue, and item checks continue regardless of Midterms, ILW, or the Activity Ban. The Freelancing Seminar targets Week 3-4 of term, well before Midterms. No event scheduling falls in a restricted window.\n\n* * *\n\n### **Dependencies**\n\n1.  **Donation drive produces a viable initial listing inventory before the exchange launches:** Dir. EXT/INT runs the drive from T-8 weeks. A minimum threshold of usable, checked, listed items should be in place before P&M is filed for the platform launch. Dir. Student Services and Dir. EXT/INT agree on this threshold number before the drive starts.\n    \n2.  **Item condition check protocol written and in use before the first listing goes live:** Every item passes through the check. Tested or untested is disclosed clearly. No-implied-warranty disclaimer is on every listing page. This is established before launch, not added after a complaint.\n    \n3.  **DAAM confirmation on SLIFE requirement at T-8 weeks:** If the OCCS SLIFE is required and this is discovered at T-4 weeks instead, there may not be enough time to clear it before the target seminar date. Dir. Documentations confirms this early.\n    \n4.  **Recording setup tested before seminar day:** Dir. Documentations owns the recording confirmation. A dry run of the recording setup happens at least two days before the seminar. If there is a technical failure on the actual day, there is no second chance for the 48-hour archive window.\n    \n5.  **Archive upload to Hub confirmed within 48 hours of seminar conclusion:** Dir. Documentations uploads the recording. Dir. Academics confirms it is live and accessible on the Hub. Both confirmations are logged in the clearance tracker. This is a hard deadline, not a target.\n    \n6.  **Disclaimer delivered verbally and on screen at the start of the seminar:** Pauline states it. It is also displayed on the projected screen behind her during the opening. Dir. Creatives prepares the on-screen version as part of the seminar's opening slide. This is not improvised on the day.\n    \n7.  **P&M cleared before any platform or seminar promotion goes public:** Dir. Creatives batches both clearances at T-4 weeks. Neither sub-project is announced before P&M approval is back from DAAM.","subprojects":"# Project 7: Student Financial Empowerment Initiative Sub-Projects\n\n## Equipment & Apparel Exchange\n\n*   **Description:** A donation channel where graduating or shifting students pass down lab gowns, calculators, and tools directly to students who need them.\n\n## Freelancing & Part-Time Work Seminar\n\n*   **Description:** A practical seminar on freelancing and legitimate part time work, so working through college doesn't have to mean a call center shift or a fast food line as the only option."},{"id":"project-8","folderName":"Project_8_Fundraising_Local_Business","name":"Project 8 Fundraising Local Business","faq":"# Fundraising & Local Business Collaboration — FAQ\n\n**Q: Where does the money from these fundraisers actually go?** A: All net proceeds are strictly divided: **70% goes directly to the Student Emergency Fund** (for crisis relief) and **30% goes to the Research Grants Pool** (to offset thesis costs). Every single peso of this split is tracked and publicly visible on the Project 2 Transparency Ledger. It is never mixed into general council funds.\n\n**Q: Why is it taking so long to finalize the partnerships?** A: University policy (DAAM) requires a strict 14-day processing lead time to approve External MOAs. Because the manual is unconfirmed on umbrella agreements, we process one MOA per business partner. We strictly comply with these rules to ensure the partnerships are legally sound.\n\n**Q: What if we don't get any partners and the fair gets cancelled? Does the Emergency Fund run out?** A: No. We have a strict Fallback Plan. If we secure zero partners in a term, we will publicly acknowledge the shortfall on the Transparency Ledger and immediately launch \"Plan B\" — an emergency crowdsourcing drive asking for direct donations from alumni and the student body to ensure the relief funds never hit zero.","description":"# Pubmat Description\n\nCommunity support means real financial aid. Our Local Business Collaboration Initiative partners with your favorite campus spots to directly fund the Student Emergency Fund (70%) and Research Grants (30%). Support the businesses that support our science scholars. Full transparency, always visible on the SCG Ledger.","executionPlan":"## **Project 8: Fundraising & Local Business Collaboration Initiative**\n\n### **Execution Plan**\n\n**Classification note:** Bucket A for the actual fundraiser events. Each event requires a Special Approval Slip (SCT, 1-3 day lead time) and an External MOA per partner (14-day DAAM lead time). The MOA lead time is the longest single processing requirement in this entire platform. It governs the whole timeline. Every other date in this project moves around it, not the other way around. Note: all financial transactions in this project require specimen signatures on file with OTREAS and the Treasurer's Exam passed by Dir. Finance. See Project 6 pre-launch checklist. Nothing moves without both.\n\nOne thing to establish upfront: this project exists to fund two other projects. The Emergency Micro-Grant Fund and the Research Grants Pool do not have a backup income source if this project underdelivers. That reality should be in the room every time a decision gets made here. Dir. EXT/INT is not running a nice-to-have community fair. They are running the financial backbone of the welfare platform.\n\n* * *\n\n### **RACI Matrix**\n\n| Area | Responsible | Accountable | Consulted | Informed |\n| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |\n| Partner Identification & Outreach | Dir. EXT/INT | President | Chief Communications | Dir. Documentations |\n| MOA Negotiation (per partner) | Dir. EXT/INT | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| MOA DAAM Submission (per partner) | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff | Dir. EXT/INT | President |\n| MOA 14-Day Lead Time Tracking | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff |  | Dir. EXT/INT |\n| SCT Submission per Event | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Operations | Dir. Finance |  |\n| Event Logistics (booth setup, venue) | Dir. Logistics | Chief of Operations | Dir. EXT/INT | Dir. Documentations |\n| Proceeds Collection and Deposit | Dir. Finance | Chief of Operations | Dir. EXT/INT | President |\n| DF Proceeds Split (70/30) | Dir. Finance | President | Chief of Staff | Dir. Documentations |\n| FRA Report Filing (per event) | Dir. Finance | Chief of Operations | Dir. Documentations | President |\n| Transparency Ledger Update (post-FAO) | Dir. Finance | Chief of Operations |  | Dir. Documentations |\n| Plan B Crowdfunding Drive | Chief Communications | President | Dir. EXT/INT | Dir. Finance |\n| P\\&M for all public-facing promotion | Dir. Creatives | Chief Communications | Dir. EXT/INT | Dir. Documentations |\n| All clearance and submission tracking | Dir. Documentations | Chief of Staff | Dir. Finance |  |\n\n* * *\n\n### **Proposed Timeline**\n\n**T-12 Weeks (Before Target Event Date)**\n\nPartner identification starts here, and the target is three to five confirmed partners per event. Dir. EXT/INT draws up a shortlist of local businesses with a natural connection to the COS student base: food businesses run by students or alumni, tutoring services, printing shops, lab supply vendors, and similar. The pitch to each partner is clear and honest: a fixed percentage of proceeds from a designated window goes to student emergency relief and research grants. The amount raised is tracked publicly on the Transparency Ledger.\n\nThree to five partners is the minimum, not the ceiling. Going after more than that from the start means that if two or three decline or drop out, the event still runs. Dir. EXT/INT and Chief Communications develop the partner pitch together. Chief Communications handles any formal outreach letters. Dir. EXT/INT handles the direct conversations.\n\nAt the same time, Dir. Finance reviews the DF ring-fence floor declared in Project 6. The projected income from this project needs to be mapped against that floor so Dir. Finance knows exactly how much the fundraising events need to generate for the micro-grant fund to have anything left to disburse after the carry-over minimum is protected.\n\n**T-10 Weeks**\n\nPartner conversations are underway. Dir. EXT/INT is in active negotiation with each shortlisted business. The target is to have three partners verbally committed by this point so MOA drafting can start.\n\nEach partner gets its own MOA. The Treasurer's Manual does not provide for a single umbrella MOA covering multiple vendors, so each agreement is drafted and processed individually. Dir. EXT/INT and Chief of Staff draft the MOA template together. The core terms are identical across partners: the event dates, the proceeds split percentage the partner is committing, how proceeds are collected and deposited, and the acknowledgment that the SCG is a student organization operating under DLSU governance. Individual partner-specific terms go in as addenda.\n\n**T-8 Weeks**\n\nThis is the hard gate. All External MOAs must be submitted to DAAM by this point at the absolute latest. The 14-day processing lead time means a submission at T-8 weeks clears by T-6 weeks, which gives enough buffer before the event to handle any resubmissions if DAAM sends something back with corrections.\n\nDir. Documentations submits every MOA as soon as it is finalized. Not in batches, not waiting for all partners to be ready at once. Each MOA goes in the moment the draft is approved by Pauline and the partner. The 14-day clock starts from individual submission, so staggering is fine.\n\nDir. EXT/INT also ensures that all External MOA submissions land by January 16 at the latest, which respects the DAAM External MOA lead time relative to the first event window. Dir. Documentations tracks each submission individually with a status column per partner in the clearance tracker.\n\n**T-6 Weeks**\n\nMOAs should be clearing from DAAM at this point. For any that come back with corrections, Dir. Documentations and Dir. EXT/INT turn them around same day and resubmit immediately.\n\nDir. Documentations files the SCT for each fundraiser event (1-3 day lead time). The SCT is filed per event, not per partner. If two events are planned, two SCTs go in.\n\nDir. Logistics begins venue coordination for the physical fair setup. Booth assignments, power access, table arrangements, and any college-level approvals for use of outdoor or common spaces go through Dir. Logistics in coordination with the Dean's Office if required.\n\nDir. Creatives starts developing promotional materials for the fair. The promotion strategy serves a dual purpose: it drives student foot traffic to the event and signals to partner businesses that the SCG is actively promoting their participation, which protects the relationship if partners question whether the collaboration is worth their time.\n\n**T-4 Weeks**\n\nAll MOAs are cleared. All SCTs confirmed. Dir. Finance confirms the projected income estimate based on confirmed partners and their committed proceeds percentages.\n\nDir. Creatives submits P&M clearance for all promotional materials. Promotion goes live once P&M clears. Dir. EXT/INT coordinates with each partner on what they are allowed to say in their own channels about the collaboration, making sure none of their promotion inadvertently bypasses the DAAM clearance requirements on the SCG side.\n\n**T-2 Weeks**\n\nFull promotional push. Dir. EXT/INT confirms final event logistics with each partner: booth location, setup time, payment collection method, and how proceeds are handed over to the SCG. All payments route through the dedicated SCG account. No personal accounts, no exception.\n\nDir. Finance prepares the income tracking sheet for the event. Every deposit is logged with the partner name, date, and amount. This feeds directly into the FRA Report after the event.\n\n**Event Week (Target: Late February, Post-Midterms)**\n\nThe Local Business Fair runs. Dir. Logistics manages physical setup. Dir. EXT/INT manages partner relations on the ground. Dir. Finance manages proceeds collection and ensures all payments are deposited into the SCG account with deposit slips filed.\n\nProceeds collection is clean and documented from the first transaction. Every peso that comes in goes through the account, not through anyone's hands. Dir. Finance brings a physical receipt book to the event if needed.\n\n**Post-Event: FRA Report and Proceeds Transfer**\n\nFAO processes all receipts first. The Transparency Ledger update goes public only after FAO confirmation. The feasibility analysis is explicit on this sequence and it is the right one. A public ledger update before FAO confirmation is a promise made on unconfirmed numbers, which is exactly the kind of thing that creates credibility problems.\n\nOnce FAO confirms all receipts, Dir. Finance files the full FRA Report within one week of the event's conclusion. The report includes: the Fundraising Activity Report, Income Statement, approved deposit slip from OTREAS, screenshot of the OTREAS email acknowledgment, compiled confirmation receipts in one PDF, and the approved A-Form with Proof of Approval.\n\nDir. Finance then formally transfers proceeds into the correct buckets: 70% into the DF Emergency Micro-Grant ring-fenced allocation, 30% into the Research Grants Pool. Both transfers are reflected on the Transparency Ledger with the date of FAO confirmation noted clearly.\n\n**Plan B: If Zero Partners Are Secured**\n\nThis is not a theoretical contingency. It is a pre-planned operational response. If Dir. EXT/INT reaches T-8 weeks without a single confirmed partner, Chief Communications activates the Emergency Crowdfunding Drive immediately. The drive is announced publicly with full transparency about why: the local business partnership model did not come together this term and the SCG is pursuing direct community support instead. The 70/30 proceeds split applies to crowdfunding income using the same logic as the fair.\n\nThe Plan B activation is not a failure to communicate externally. It is the council being honest about what happened and moving quickly to protect the funds that Project 6 depends on.\n\n**Blackout Compliance**\n\nThe target event window is late February, immediately after Midterms end (Feb 21). This gives the maximum available term window after the GOSM Defense period and Midterms, while still landing before ILW (Mar 2-7) and the Activity Ban (Mar 30). MOA submissions at T-8 weeks fall in early January, well before any blackout restrictions. P&M clearance at T-4 weeks falls in early February, also clear. No event activity falls inside a restricted window.\n\n* * *\n\n### **Dependencies**\n\n1.  **Three confirmed partners minimum before any MOA is drafted:** Dir. EXT/INT and Pauline agree on a partner floor before outreach begins. Going into MOA drafting with one confirmed partner and hoping for more is not a strategy. The floor is three. If only two partners confirm by T-10 weeks, outreach expands before MOA drafting starts.\n    \n2.  **All External MOAs submitted to DAAM by T-8 weeks, no later than January 16:** The 14-day processing requirement makes this the most time-sensitive filing in the entire platform. Dir. Documentations tracks each MOA individually from the moment drafting begins. A single MOA submitted late can delay an entire partner's participation.\n    \n3.  **All proceeds routed through the dedicated SCG account, no exceptions:** Dir. Finance establishes this as a standing rule before the first partner conversation happens. It goes into every MOA as a stated term. Partners know before they sign that payment collection follows the SCG's formal financial process.\n    \n4.  **FRA Report filed within one week of event conclusion, after FAO confirmation:** Dir. Finance leads this with Dir. Documentations compiling the receipt PDF. If net proceeds exceed ₱5,000, the full FRA Report is required. Given the fundraising targets, it almost certainly will be. The report is prepared in advance with all fields ready, so only the confirmed figures need to be filled in after FAO confirmation.\n    \n5.  **Transparency Ledger update goes out after FAO confirmation, not before:** Dir. Finance and Dir. Documentations both understand this sequencing. The 48-hour public communication standard from Project 3 applies here, but the clock starts from FAO confirmation, not from the close of the event.\n    \n6.  **70/30 split transferred formally into the correct allocations before any disbursement is made from either pool:** Dir. Finance completes the transfer and logs it on the Transparency Ledger before Project 6 or the Research Grants Portal draws from the new income. The split is not approximate. It is exact, documented, and public.\n    \n7.  **Plan B Crowdfunding Drive brief prepared in advance:** Chief Communications drafts the Plan B announcement before it is needed. If the trigger condition is reached, the response goes out within 24 hours, not after a week of internal deliberation. The draft exists, the channels are identified, and the activation decision belongs to Pauline alone.","subprojects":"# Project 8: Fundraising & Local Business Collaboration Initiative Sub-Projects\n\n## Fundraiser Events & Local Business Partnerships\n\n*   **Description:** A recurring partnership program with local businesses near campus. A percentage of proceeds from a promotion period goes to the Emergency Fund (70%) and Research Grants (30%).\n*   **Timeline:** Event/Partnerships. Requires Special Approval Slip (SCT) 1-3 days + External MOA 14 days per partner.\n*   **Feasibility:** Feasible if aiming for 3-5 small partners. Fallback plan: Emergency Crowdfunding Drive if 0 partners are secured."}],"preActs":{"project-1":{"name":"Project 1 Student Resource Hub","files":[{"filename":"README.md","content":"# Pre-Acts & Clearances\n## Student Resource & Academic Support Hub\n\n### General Status\nThe Student Resource & Academic Support Hub, including all its internal features (Portals, Calculators, Directories, Survival Guides, Libraries), is classified as a **Standing Platform Feature (Bucket B)**. \n\nTherefore, these items **DO NOT** require formal Pre-Act documentation (APS/SLIFE forms) as they are not physical or synchronous \"activities\" with attendees.\n\n### Required Clearances\nInstead of Pre-Acts, every sub-item in this folder requires:\n1. **P&M (Publicity Material) Approval:** Must be submitted with a **24-hour lead time** prior to posting any promotional materials on social media.\n2. **GOSM Posting Clearance:** Must be secured before official public rollout.\n\n*Exception Note:* If the Research Grants & Funding Portal begins disbursing real council funds to students, a **Special Approval Slip (SCT)** with a 1–3 day lead time will be required strictly for the financial disbursement process.\n\n---\n\n### Changelog\n*Log every P&M submission, status update, and GOSM clearance here to maintain a strict paper trail.*\n\n| Date | Item / Action | Status | Notes |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n"}]},"project-2":{"name":"Project 2 Semana ng Siyensya","files":[{"filename":"README.md","content":"# Pre-Acts (Internal)\n\n## 1. Classification\n- **Type**: Major College Event (On-Ground & Online)\n- **Primary Beneficiary**: Food Security Pantry & Emergency Micro-Grant\n- **Budget Requisition**: ₱15,000 (Merchandise Downpayment, Logistics)\n\n## 2. Required Clearances\n- [ ] **SLIFE Approval**: Pending submission 1 month prior.\n- [ ] **SDA Clearance**: Required for E-Sports event (Games and Amusement regulations).\n- [ ] **Dean's Office Endorsement**: Required for Academic Incentives integration.\n- [ ] **GOSM Registration**: Completed.\n- [ ] **P&M Clearance**: Pending material designs.\n"}]},"project-3":{"name":"Project 3 Transparency Platform","files":[{"filename":"README.md","content":"# Pre-Acts & Clearances\n## Transparency & Accountability Platform\n\n### General Status\nThe Transparency & Accountability Platform, including the Grievance Channel, Ledger, Charter, and Suggestion Tab, is classified as a **Standing Platform Feature (Bucket B)**. \n\nTherefore, these items **DO NOT** require formal Pre-Act documentation (APS/SLIFE forms) as they are not physical or synchronous \"activities\" with attendees.\n\n### Required Clearances\nInstead of Pre-Acts, every sub-item in this folder requires:\n1. **P&M (Publicity Material) Approval:** Must be submitted with a **24-hour lead time** prior to posting any promotional materials on social media.\n2. **GOSM Posting Clearance:** Must be secured before official public rollout.\n\n---\n\n### Changelog\n*Log every P&M submission, status update, and GOSM clearance here to maintain a strict paper trail.*\n\n| Date | Item / Action | Status | Notes |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n"}]},"project-4":{"name":"Project 4 Inclusion Accessibility","files":[{"filename":"FSL_Training_PPR.md","content":"# PROJECT PROPOSAL (PPR)\n## Filipino Sign Language (FSL) Training Program\n\n**I. ACTIVITY DETAILS**\n- **Title of Activity:** Filipino Sign Language (FSL) Training Program\n- **Nature of Activity:** Community Development\n- **Type of Activity:** Seminar / Workshop\n- **ENMP/ENP:** 10 / 50\n- **Date:** February 14, 2027\n- **Time:** 1:00 PM - 5:00 PM\n- **Venue:** Gokongwei Hall Room 201 (or equivalent)\n- **Project Head(s):** Director for External and Internal Linkages\n\n**II. BRIEF CONTEXT/PERSPECTIVE OF THE ACTIVITY**\n*(Part 1)* The Deaf and hard-of-hearing community remains an afterthought in our classrooms and laboratories. Often, there is a distinct lack of communicators within the student body capable of basic conversational FSL, leading to systemic exclusion in collaborative academic spaces.\n*(Part 2)* This exclusion exists because FSL is rarely integrated into standard curriculum or extracurricular training. We feel that science must be accessible to everyone, and communication barriers directly hinder the academic experience of marginalized students. \n*(Part 3)* By partnering with a recognized Deaf community organization, we will equip student leaders and volunteers with foundational FSL skills. This ensures that our college takes a concrete step toward becoming a truly inclusive environment.\n\n**III. OBJECTIVES**\n1. To train 50 student leaders and volunteers in basic conversational Filipino Sign Language.\n2. To establish a long-term partnership with a recognized Deaf community organization.\n3. To foster an inclusive laboratory and classroom environment by reducing communication barriers.\n\n**IV. COMPREHENSIVE PROGRAM DESIGN**\n- 1:00 PM - 1:30 PM: Registration\n- 1:30 PM - 2:00 PM: Introduction to Deaf Culture & Etiquette\n- 2:00 PM - 4:00 PM: Basic FSL Instruction (Alphabet, Greetings, Academic terms)\n- 4:00 PM - 4:30 PM: Interactive Practice Session\n- 4:30 PM - 4:55 PM: Closing & AET Evaluation\n- 4:55 PM - 5:00 PM: Clean-up\n\n**V. BREAKDOWN OF EXPENSES**\n- Honorarium for Partner Organization Instructors: Php 5,000.00\n- **Total:** Php 5,000.00\n\n**VI. ALLOCATION OF EXPENSES**\n- Organizational Funds: Php 5,000.00\n- **Total:** Php 5,000.00\n\n**VII. PROJECTED INCOME**\n*THIS ACTIVITY IS NOT A FUNDRAISING/SELLING ACTIVITY; THUS, IT WILL NOT INCUR INCOME OR LOSS.*\n\n**VIII. SUMMARY OF FUNDS**\n- Accumulated Operational Funds: N/A\n- Total Cash for Disbursement: Php 5,000.00\n- Less: Total Projected Expenses: Php 5,000.00\n- **REMAINING BALANCE:** Php 0.00\n\n**IX. PROVISIONS FOR PROFIT AND LOSS**\nThe Chief Operating Officer and Chairperson for Finance shall be held liable and will shoulder any remaining balance incurred by the project.\n"},{"filename":"Lab_Audit_Letter.md","content":"**Date:** January 27, 2027\n\n**To:** \nDr. [Insert Name]\nDean, College of Science\n\n[Insert Name]\nDirector, Physical Facilities Management\n\n**Thru:** \nMr. James B. Laxa\nDirector, Office of Student LIFE\n\n**From:** \n[Insert Name]\nDirector for Advocacy, College of Science Government\n\n**Re:** Request for Formal Access for Laboratory Accessibility Audit\n\nGreetings in St. La Salle!\n\nThe College of Science Government (SCG) is initiating a comprehensive Laboratory Accessibility Audit to identify and document physical barriers that hinder students with disabilities from fully participating in laboratory classes. This initiative aligns with the University's commitment to inclusive education.\n\nIn line with this, we formally request access to conduct a student-led physical walkthrough and audit of all College of Science laboratory facilities from **March 9 to March 13, 2027**. \n\nUpon completion of the audit, we will submit a formal report detailing our findings and recommended fixes. **We respectfully request a formal response and/or remediation plan from your respective offices within ninety (90) days of the report's submission (Deadline: May 2, 2027).** Please be advised that in the interest of transparency and student welfare, if no substantive response or remediation plan is provided by this 90-day deadline, the council will publish the full audit report publicly on our Transparency Platform.\n\nShould you have any questions or clarifications, you may contact me at [Email Address] & [Mobile Number].\n\nWe look forward to your favorable response. Thank you very much!\n\nSincerely,\n\n[Insert Name]\nDirector for Advocacy, SCG\n\nNoted By:\n\n[Insert Name]\nCollege President, SCG\n"},{"filename":"README.md","content":"# Pre-Acts & Clearances\n## Inclusion, Accessibility & Representation Initiative\n\n### General Status\nThis project is a hybrid of Bucket A (Real Activities) and Bucket B (Standing Platforms). \n\n1. **Filipino Sign Language Training Program:** Bucket A. Requires General Pre-Activity (APS) forms (4-6 days lead time) and a formal External MOA (14 days lead time).\n2. **Laboratory Accessibility Audit:** Bucket A. Requires Letters and Requests (2-3 days lead time) for the physical walkthroughs.\n3. **Women and Minority in STEM Archive:** Bucket B. Requires ONLY P&M (Publicity Material) approval (24-hour lead time) and strict opt-in consent forms.\n\n### Included Documents\n- `FSL_Training_PPR.md` — Project Proposal Report for the FSL Training Program.\n- `Lab_Audit_Letter.md` — Formal request letter to the Dean's Office and PFM establishing the 90-day deadline.\n\n---\n\n### Changelog\n*Log every Pre-Act submission, MOA status, and P&M approval here to maintain a strict paper trail.*\n\n| Date | Item / Action | Status | Notes |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n"}]},"project-5":{"name":"Project 5 Queer Trans Education","files":[{"filename":"PreColonial_History_Session_PPR.md","content":"# PROJECT PROPOSAL (PPR)\n## Pre-Colonial Gender & Trans History Session\n\n**I. ACTIVITY DETAILS**\n- **Title of Activity:** Pre-Colonial Gender & Trans History Session\n- **Nature of Activity:** Awareness Campaign\n- **Type of Activity:** Seminar / Workshop\n- **ENMP/ENP:** 10 / 100\n- **Date:** March 11, 2027\n- **Time:** 2:00 PM - 5:00 PM\n- **Venue:** Yuchangco Hall (or equivalent)\n- **Project Head(s):** Director for National Affairs\n\n**II. BRIEF CONTEXT/PERSPECTIVE OF THE ACTIVITY**\n*(Part 1)* There is a persistent misconception that queer and trans identities are a modern, Western import. This erasure of pre-colonial Philippine history contributes to the marginalization of LGBTQ+ Filipinos today.\n*(Part 2)* Without understanding the historical reverence for gender diversity in our own culture—such as the role of the Babaylan and Asog—students are deprived of the cultural context that proves queer identities are inherently Filipino.\n*(Part 3)* This session will explore gender diversity in pre-colonial Philippine history, providing students with the historical backing to understand that the conversation around queer rights is not new, but rather a returning one.\n\n**III. OBJECTIVES**\n1. To educate 100 students on the history of gender diversity in the pre-colonial Philippines.\n2. To dispel the myth that queer and trans identities are a Western influence.\n3. To contextualize modern LGBTQ+ rights movements (e.g., the SOGIE bill) within Philippine historical precedents.\n\n**IV. COMPREHENSIVE PROGRAM DESIGN**\n- 2:00 PM - 2:30 PM: Registration\n- 2:30 PM - 3:30 PM: Main Lecture: The Babaylan, Asog, and Pre-Colonial Gender Diversity\n- 3:30 PM - 4:15 PM: Moderated Panel Discussion\n- 4:15 PM - 4:45 PM: Open Forum / Q&A\n- 4:45 PM - 4:55 PM: Closing & AET Evaluation\n- 4:55 PM - 5:00 PM: Clean-up\n\n**V. BREAKDOWN OF EXPENSES**\n- Speaker Tokens (Certificates & University Merchandise): Php 1,500.00\n- **Total:** Php 1,500.00\n\n**VI. ALLOCATION OF EXPENSES**\n- Organizational Funds: Php 1,500.00\n- **Total:** Php 1,500.00\n\n**VII. PROJECTED INCOME**\n*THIS ACTIVITY IS NOT A FUNDRAISING/SELLING ACTIVITY; THUS, IT WILL NOT INCUR INCOME OR LOSS.*\n\n**VIII. SUMMARY OF FUNDS**\n- Accumulated Operational Funds: N/A\n- Total Cash for Disbursement: Php 1,500.00\n- Less: Total Projected Expenses: Php 1,500.00\n- **REMAINING BALANCE:** Php 0.00\n\n**IX. PROVISIONS FOR PROFIT AND LOSS**\nThe Chief Operating Officer and Chairperson for Finance shall be held liable and will shoulder any remaining balance incurred by the project.\n"},{"filename":"Queer_Identity_Forum_PPR.md","content":"# PROJECT PROPOSAL (PPR)\n## Queer Identity Science Forum\n\n**I. ACTIVITY DETAILS**\n- **Title of Activity:** Queer Identity Science Forum\n- **Nature of Activity:** Awareness Campaign\n- **Type of Activity:** Seminar / Workshop with Distinguished Speakers\n- **ENMP/ENP:** 10 / 100\n- **Date:** February 11, 2027\n- **Time:** 2:00 PM - 5:00 PM\n- **Venue:** Yuchangco Hall (or equivalent)\n- **Project Head(s):** Director for Advocacy\n\n**II. BRIEF CONTEXT/PERSPECTIVE OF THE ACTIVITY**\n*(Part 1)* Queer and trans identities are frequently invalidated by claims that they are \"unnatural\" or \"unscientific.\" In a College of Science, allowing prejudice to masquerade as objective fact is unacceptable.\n*(Part 2)* The proliferation of these myths stems from a lack of accessible, rigorous education on the biology, sociology, and psychology of gender and sexuality. Students need a space where their identities are validated by actual science, not debated as opinions.\n*(Part 3)* By inviting credentialed academics to present peer-reviewed research, this forum will counter anti-LGBTQ+ prejudice with undeniable academic evidence, fostering a safer, more informed campus culture.\n\n**III. OBJECTIVES**\n1. To educate 100 students on the biological, psychological, and sociological realities of queer and trans identities.\n2. To provide a platform for credentialed academics to share peer-reviewed research countering gender essentialism.\n3. To foster an unapologetically affirming academic environment for LGBTQ+ students in the College of Science.\n\n**IV. COMPREHENSIVE PROGRAM DESIGN**\n- 2:00 PM - 2:30 PM: Registration\n- 2:30 PM - 3:15 PM: Speaker 1 (The Biology of Sex & Gender)\n- 3:15 PM - 4:00 PM: Speaker 2 (The Sociology of Queer Identities)\n- 4:00 PM - 4:45 PM: Open Forum / Q&A\n- 4:45 PM - 4:55 PM: Closing & AET Evaluation\n- 4:55 PM - 5:00 PM: Clean-up\n\n**V. BREAKDOWN OF EXPENSES**\n- Speaker Tokens (Certificates & University Merchandise): Php 1,500.00\n- **Total:** Php 1,500.00\n\n**VI. ALLOCATION OF EXPENSES**\n- Organizational Funds: Php 1,500.00\n- **Total:** Php 1,500.00\n\n**VII. PROJECTED INCOME**\n*THIS ACTIVITY IS NOT A FUNDRAISING/SELLING ACTIVITY; THUS, IT WILL NOT INCUR INCOME OR LOSS.*\n\n**VIII. SUMMARY OF FUNDS**\n- Accumulated Operational Funds: N/A\n- Total Cash for Disbursement: Php 1,500.00\n- Less: Total Projected Expenses: Php 1,500.00\n- **REMAINING BALANCE:** Php 0.00\n\n**IX. PROVISIONS FOR PROFIT AND LOSS**\nThe Chief Operating Officer and Chairperson for Finance shall be held liable and will shoulder any remaining balance incurred by the project.\n"},{"filename":"README.md","content":"# Pre-Acts & Clearances\n## Queer & Trans Identity Education Series\n\n### General Status\nThis project includes both Bucket A (Real Activities) and Bucket B (Standing Platforms) components.\n\n1. **Queer Identity Science Forum:** Bucket A. Requires General Pre-Activity (APS) forms (4-6 days lead time).\n2. **Pre-Colonial Gender & Trans History Session:** Bucket A. Requires General Pre-Activity (APS) forms (4-6 days lead time).\n3. **Shanghay Laya Website:** Bucket B. Requires ONLY P&M (Publicity Material) approval (24-hour lead time).\n\n### Included Documents\n- `Queer_Identity_Forum_PPR.md` — Project Proposal Report for the Science Forum.\n- `PreColonial_History_Session_PPR.md` — Project Proposal Report for the History Session.\n\n---\n\n### Changelog\n*Log every Pre-Act submission and P&M approval here to maintain a strict paper trail.*\n\n| Date | Item / Action | Status | Notes |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n"}]},"project-6":{"name":"Project 6 Emergency Response","files":[{"filename":"README.md","content":"# Pre-Acts & Clearances\n## Student Emergency Response & Relief Program\n\n### General Status\nAll components of this project are classified as **Bucket B — Standing Platform Features**.\n\n1. **Student Emergency Fund & Calamity System:** Bucket B.\n2. **COS Pantry / Community Supplies:** Bucket B.\n3. **Welfare Outreach Registry:** Bucket B.\n\nBecause these are ongoing, internal, and non-event operational features, they **do not require** formal Pre-Activity forms (APS/ADM). They are cleared purely via Publicity & Marketing (P&M) procedures for their informational campaigns (24-hour lead time) and internal budget processing.\n\n*No formal APS/ADM templates have been generated for this folder.*\n\n---\n\n### Changelog\n*Log every P&M approval and significant budget clearance here to maintain a strict paper trail.*\n\n| Date | Item / Action | Status | Notes |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n"}]},"project-7":{"name":"Project 7 Financial Empowerment","files":[{"filename":"Freelancing_Seminar_PPR.md","content":"# PROJECT PROPOSAL (PPR)\n## Freelancing & Part-Time Work Seminar\n\n**I. ACTIVITY DETAILS**\n- **Title of Activity:** Freelancing & Part-Time Work Seminar\n- **Nature of Activity:** Student Welfare / Skill-Building\n- **Type of Activity:** Seminar / Workshop\n- **ENMP/ENP:** 10 / 150\n- **Date:** February 12, 2027\n- **Time:** 2:00 PM - 5:00 PM\n- **Venue:** Andrew Gonzalez Hall (or equivalent large venue)\n- **Project Head(s):** Director for Student Services\n\n**II. BRIEF CONTEXT/PERSPECTIVE OF THE ACTIVITY**\n*(Part 1)* The cost of a science degree extends far beyond tuition—lab fees, manuals, and specialized equipment create a heavy burden. An increasing number of students are turning to part-time work and freelancing to fund their own education.\n*(Part 2)* However, many students lack the foundational knowledge to navigate the freelance market, risking exploitation, burnout, or academic failure.\n*(Part 3)* This seminar will provide practical, lived-experience insights on balancing academics with part-time work, securing clients, and managing time effectively, equipping self-funding students with the tools they need to survive and thrive.\n\n**III. OBJECTIVES**\n1. To equip 150 students with practical strategies for securing and managing part-time freelance work.\n2. To provide a realistic framework for balancing heavy academic science workloads with employment.\n3. To generate a permanent video archive of the seminar for the Student Resource Hub.\n\n**IV. COMPREHENSIVE PROGRAM DESIGN**\n- 2:00 PM - 2:30 PM: Registration\n- 2:30 PM - 2:40 PM: Opening Remarks & Disclaimer (Lived Experience, No Endorsements)\n- 2:40 PM - 3:40 PM: Main Lecture: Surviving Science as a Working Student (Speaker: Pauline)\n- 3:40 PM - 4:20 PM: Open Forum / Q&A\n- 4:20 PM - 4:45 PM: Recording Sign-off & AET Evaluation\n- 4:45 PM - 5:00 PM: Clean-up\n\n**V. BREAKDOWN OF EXPENSES**\n- Venue Technical Fees (Microphones/Projector): Php 0.00 (Standard University Provision)\n- Speaker Tokens: Php 0.00 (Internal SCG Speaker)\n- **Total:** Php 0.00\n\n**VI. ALLOCATION OF EXPENSES**\n- Organizational Funds: Php 0.00\n- **Total:** Php 0.00\n\n**VII. PROJECTED INCOME**\n*THIS ACTIVITY IS NOT A FUNDRAISING/SELLING ACTIVITY; THUS, IT WILL NOT INCUR INCOME OR LOSS.*\n\n**VIII. SUMMARY OF FUNDS**\n- Accumulated Operational Funds: N/A\n- Total Cash for Disbursement: Php 0.00\n- Less: Total Projected Expenses: Php 0.00\n- **REMAINING BALANCE:** Php 0.00\n\n**IX. PROVISIONS FOR PROFIT AND LOSS**\nThe Chief Operating Officer and Chairperson for Finance shall be held liable and will shoulder any remaining balance incurred by the project.\n"},{"filename":"README.md","content":"# Pre-Acts & Clearances\n## Student Financial Empowerment Initiative\n\n### General Status\nThis project contains a mix of Bucket A (Real Activities) and Bucket B (Standing Platforms).\n\n1. **Equipment & Apparel Exchange (Uniform/Lab Gown Bank):** Bucket B. This is an ongoing platform feature managed via the Hub. Requires only P&M approval for promotional materials.\n2. **Freelancing & Part-Time Work Seminar:** Bucket A. This is a live event that requires a General Pre-Activity (APS) form (4-6 days lead time).\n\n### Included Documents\n- `Freelancing_Seminar_PPR.md` — Project Proposal Report for the live seminar.\n\n---\n\n### Changelog\n*Log every Pre-Act submission and P&M approval here to maintain a strict paper trail.*\n\n| Date | Item / Action | Status | Notes |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n"}]},"project-8":{"name":"Project 8 Fundraising Local Business","files":[{"filename":"Local_Business_Fair_PPR.md","content":"# PROJECT PROPOSAL (PPR)\n## Local Business Support Fair (Fundraiser)\n\n**I. ACTIVITY DETAILS**\n- **Title of Activity:** Local Business Support Fair\n- **Nature of Activity:** Fundraising & Partnership\n- **Type of Activity:** Selling / Bazaar\n- **ENMP/ENP:** 15 / 500\n- **Date:** February 25 - 27, 2027\n- **Time:** 9:00 AM - 5:00 PM\n- **Venue:** Marian Quadrangle (or equivalent open grounds)\n- **Project Head(s):** Director for External and Internal Linkages\n\n**II. BRIEF CONTEXT/PERSPECTIVE OF THE ACTIVITY**\n*(Part 1)* The Student Emergency Fund and the Research Grants Pool require sustainable, reliable funding to remain operational. Relying solely on internal organizational funds limits the scope of aid we can provide.\n*(Part 2)* By partnering with local businesses around the campus, we can host a centralized fundraising fair. This provides valuable marketing and sales for our local partners while generating direct proceeds for our student welfare programs.\n*(Part 3)* This fair will act as the primary capital generator for the term, directly converting community engagement into financial support for science students in need.\n\n**III. OBJECTIVES**\n1. To generate capital to fund the Student Emergency Fund and the Research Grants Pool.\n2. To provide a high-visibility marketing and sales platform for 3 to 5 local business partners.\n3. To foster stronger ties between the College of Science student body and the local campus business community.\n\n**IV. COMPREHENSIVE PROGRAM DESIGN**\n*(Applicable for each day of the 3-day fair)*\n- 8:00 AM - 9:00 AM: Ingress and Booth Setup\n- 9:00 AM - 5:00 PM: Fair Operations (Selling, Promotions, Student Engagement)\n- 5:00 PM - 6:00 PM: Egress and Daily Clean-up\n- 6:00 PM - 7:00 PM: Daily Remittance and Accounting of Proceeds\n\n**V. BREAKDOWN OF EXPENSES**\n- Physical Booth Rentals (Tents/Tables): Php 3,000.00\n- **Total:** Php 3,000.00\n\n**VI. ALLOCATION OF EXPENSES**\n- Organizational Funds: Php 3,000.00\n- **Total:** Php 3,000.00\n\n**VII. PROJECTED INCOME**\n- Projected Booth Fees / Percentage of Sales from 5 Partners: Php 10,000.00\n- **Total Projected Income:** Php 10,000.00\n\n**VIII. SUMMARY OF FUNDS**\n- Accumulated Operational Funds: N/A\n- Total Cash for Disbursement: Php 3,000.00\n- Less: Total Projected Expenses: Php 3,000.00\n- **REMAINING BALANCE:** Php 0.00\n\n**IX. PROVISIONS FOR PROFIT AND LOSS**\nAll net proceeds (Projected: Php 7,000.00) will be strictly divided: 70% to the Student Emergency Fund and 30% to the Research Grants Pool. The Chief Operating Officer and Chairperson for Finance shall be held liable and will shoulder any remaining balance or losses incurred by the project.\n"},{"filename":"README.md","content":"# Pre-Acts & Clearances\n## Fundraising & Local Business Collaboration Initiative\n\n### General Status\nThis project falls entirely under **Bucket A (Real Activities)** as it involves formal external partnerships and physical fundraising events on campus.\n\n1. **Local Business Support Fair:** Bucket A. Requires a General Pre-Activity (APS) form (4-6 days lead time).\n2. **External Partnerships:** Bucket A. Each partnership requires an External Memorandum of Agreement (MOA), which carries a strict 14-day lead time via DAAM.\n\n### Included Documents\n- `Local_Business_Fair_PPR.md` — Project Proposal Report for the fundraiser event.\n\n---\n\n### Changelog\n*Log every Pre-Act submission and P&M approval here to maintain a strict paper trail.*\n\n| Date | Item / Action | Status | Notes |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n| | | | |\n"}]}},"globalDocs":[{"filename":"00_Comms_Protocol.md","name":"Comms Protocol","content":"# Internal Communications Protocol\n\n## 1. Reporting Cadences\n- **Director-to-Chief (Weekly):** Every Friday by 5:00 PM, Directors must submit a bulleted status update on their assigned projects to their respective Chief (Chief of Staff, Operations, or Communications). Updates must explicitly highlight blocked tasks.\n- **Chief-to-President (Biweekly):** Chiefs will consolidate reports and meet with the President biweekly to assess overall platform health, DAAM approval statuses, and budget burn rates.\n\n## 2. Escalation Path\nIf a Director is stuck, a dependency is blocked, or a hard deadline (e.g., DAAM 14-day rule) is at risk, follow this exact escalation path:\n\n1. **24 Hours Blocked:** Director notifies their respective Chief via the internal messaging channel. The Chief attempts to unblock the issue directly.\n2. **48 Hours Blocked:** The Chief escalates the issue to the President.\n3. **72 Hours Blocked / Imminent Blackout Risk:** The President calls an emergency alignment meeting with the affected Director and Chief to trigger the fallback plan (e.g., moving an event post-midterms, triggering Plan B funding).\n4. **Administrative Blockade:** If the blockage is due to administrative non-cooperation (e.g., Dean refuses LOA, DAAM sits on a Pre-Act), the President and Chief of Staff will assume direct control of communications with the admin office to force a resolution.\n"},{"filename":"00_Handover_Notes.md","name":"Handover Notes","content":"# Handover Notes\n\nIf a responsible Director is suddenly unavailable due to academic workload, health, or turnover, this document outlines who assumes immediate operational control of their project and where all necessary files are located.\n\n### Project 1: Student Resource & Academic Support Hub\n- **Primary:** Director for Academics / Director for R&D\n- **Fallback:** Chief of Staff\n- **File Location:** `/Project_1_Student_Resource_Hub/`\n- **Key Note:** Ensure the OSFA verification dates and Dean's LOA are maintained. Do not let the Scholarship Calculator fall out of date.\n\n### Project 2: Semana ng Siyensya\n- **Primary:** Director for Academics / Chief of Operations\n- **Fallback:** President\n- **File Location:** `/Project_2_Semana_ng_Siyensya/`\n- **Key Note:** Ensure venue bookings and college approvals are secured at least 30 days prior.\n\n### Project 3: Transparency & Accountability Platform\n- **Primary:** Director for Student Services / Director for Finance\n- **Fallback:** Chief of Staff\n- **File Location:** `/Project_3_Transparency_Platform/`\n- **Key Note:** The 72-hour ledger update mandate cannot pause. If Dir. Finance is out, the Chief of Staff temporarily logs expenditures.\n\n### Project 4: Inclusion, Accessibility & Representation Initiative\n- **Primary:** Director for Advocacy\n- **Fallback:** Chief of Staff\n- **File Location:** `/Project_4_Inclusion_Accessibility/`\n- **Key Note:** Ensure the 90-day response deadline on the Lab Audit is still being actively tracked against the Dean's Office.\n\n### Project 5: Queer & Trans Identity Education Series\n- **Primary:** Director for Advocacy\n- **Fallback:** Director for National Affairs\n- **File Location:** `/Project_5_Queer_Trans_Education/`\n- **Key Note:** Maintain strict adherence to the medically-reviewed disclaimers on the Shanghay Laya website. Never skip the vetting of speaker credentials.\n\n### Project 6: Student Emergency Response & Relief Program\n- **Primary:** Director for Student Services\n- **Fallback:** Director for Logistics / Chief of Operations\n- **File Location:** `/Project_6_Emergency_Response/`\n- **Key Note:** The COS Pantry cannot close. Chief of Operations assumes physical restocking duties and usage logging immediately.\n\n### Project 7: Student Financial Empowerment Initiative\n- **Primary:** Director for Student Services\n- **Fallback:** Director for EXT/INT Linkages\n- **File Location:** `/Project_7_Financial_Empowerment/`\n- **Key Note:** Ensure the Freelancing Seminar archive is safely uploaded to the Hub within 48 hours.\n\n### Project 8: Fundraising & Local Business Collaboration Initiative\n- **Primary:** Director for EXT/INT Linkages\n- **Fallback:** Chief Communications\n- **File Location:** `/Project_8_Fundraising_Local_Business/`\n- **Key Note:** If a partner drops out, the 70/30 split logic remains identical. Chief Comms triggers the Plan B Crowdfunding Drive if the 0-partner fallback is reached.\n"},{"filename":"00_Master_Execution_Tracker.md","name":"Master Execution Tracker","content":"# Master Execution Tracker\r\n\r\n## 1. Project Status Overview\r\n| Project | Owning Director | Current Phase | Next Action Due |\r\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\r\n| P1: Student Resource Hub | Dir. Academics | Pre-Launch | OSFA Criteria Verification |\r\n| P2: Semana ng Siyensya | Dir. Academics | Pre-Launch | Faculty Coordination for Incentives |\r\n| P3: Transparency Platform | Dir. Student Services | Pre-Launch | Secure External Mediator |\r\n| P4: Inclusion & Access | Dir. Advocacy | Pre-Launch | Secure FSL External MOA |\r\n| P5: Queer & Trans Education | Dir. Advocacy | Pre-Launch | Legal Disclaimer Review |\r\n| P6: Emergency Response | Dir. Student Services | Pre-Launch | Finalize Calamity Tiers Budget |\r\n| P7: Financial Empowerment | Dir. Student Services | Pre-Launch | Donation Drive for Equipment |\r\n| P8: Fundraising & Local Biz | Dir. EXT/INT | Pre-Launch | Pitch 3-5 Partners |\r\n\r\n## 2. Chief Verification Responsibilities\r\n- **Chief of Staff:** Oversees P1, P3, and P4. Verifies academic alignment, legal compliance (e.g., student rights, grievances), and administrative negotiations (e.g., Dean's LOA, PFM Access).\r\n- **Chief of Operations:** Oversees P6 and P8. Verifies logistical execution (e.g., Pantry stocking, Fundraiser booth setups, emergency fund physical disbursements).\r\n- **Chief Communications:** Oversees P5, P7, and P8. Verifies brand integrity, P&M quality, and ensures strict adherence to legal/disclaimer framing across all public platforms.\r\n\r\n## 3. General Assembly Talking Points (Pauline)\r\n- Rooting policy in systemic reform, not performative events.\r\n- Shifting from \"we care about students\" to building hard digital infrastructure (Resource Hub, Transparency Platform).\r\n- Treating the financial burden of a science degree as a solvable problem (Emergency Fund, Equipment Exchange, Freelancing Seminar).\r\n- Demanding unapologetic inclusivity grounded in science and history (FSL Training, Lab Audits, Queer/Trans Education).\r\n- Proving self-sustainability through Local Business Collaboration.\r\n\r\n## 4. Timeline Fallback Matrix\r\n*Key: ✅ Done | 🟡 In Progress | ⬜ Not Started | 🔴 Blackout*\r\n\r\n| Phase | P1 | P2 | P3 | P4 | P5 | P6 | P7 | P8 |\r\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\r\n| Phase 1: Planning & Setup | 🟡 | 🟡 | 🟡 | 🟡 | 🟡 | 🟡 | 🟡 | 🟡 |\r\n| Phase 2: Pre-Acts / DAAM | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ |\r\n| Phase 3: Launch / Execution | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ |\r\n| Midterms Week (Feb 16-21)| 🔴 | 🔴 | 🔴 | 🔴 | 🔴 | 🔴 | 🔴 | 🔴 |\r\n| Post-Midterms Execution | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ | ⬜ |\r\n| ILW (Mar 2-7) | 🔴 | 🔴 | 🔴 | 🔴 | 🔴 | 🔴 | 🔴 | 🔴 |\r\n\r\n## 5. Officer Onboarding Snapshots\r\n- **Director for Academics:** You are managing the Student Resource Hub. Your primary job is ensuring academic data (calculators, flowcharts, syllabi) is continuously validated against official Admin sources so we never mislead students.\r\n- **Director for Student Services:** You are the frontline for student welfare. You manage the Transparency Platform (Grievances), the Emergency Response Program, and the Financial Empowerment platforms. Your focus is rapid execution and strict data privacy.\r\n- **Director for Advocacy:** You translate inclusion into structural change. You lead the Inclusion & Accessibility Initiative and the Queer & Trans Education Series, ensuring all advocacy is grounded in hard science and documented history.\r\n- **Director for R&D:** You manage the Research Job Board and Grants Portal. Your role is treating undergraduate research as a professional endeavor, verifying listings, and facilitating smooth grant disbursements.\r\n- **Director for EXT/INT Linkages:** You are our primary partnership builder. You will negotiate the FSL Training MOA and pitch to local businesses for Project 8 to secure sustainable funding for our grant pools.\r\n- **Director for Creatives:** You manage the visual identity of the entire platform. Every platform requires clean, accessible design that adheres to the `genesis-DESIGN` visual tokens.\r\n- **Director for Documentations:** You are the keeper of the paper trail. You track every Pre-Act and P&M submission and ensure all event archives (e.g., Freelancing Seminar) are successfully uploaded.\r\n"},{"filename":"00_PreAct_Classification.md","name":"PreAct Classification","content":"# Pre-Act Classification\r\n\r\nThis document categorizes all sub-projects into two buckets to clarify documentation requirements and lead times according to the DAAM Operations Manual.\r\n\r\n## Bucket A — Real Activities (Requires Pre-Acts / Formal Processing)\r\nThese items are activities that happen at a specific time and place.\r\n\r\n| Project | Sub-Project / Activity | Documentation Type & Lead Time |\r\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\r\n| Project 2 | Academic Competitions (Quiz Bee, Research, Spelling Bee) | General Pre-Activity (APS): 4–6 days |\r\n| Project 2 | COS Discord Gaming Night | General Pre-Activity (APS): 4–6 days |\r\n| Project 2 | Department Merchandise Drive | SAS (SCT): 1–3 days |\r\n| Project 4 | Filipino Sign Language Training Program | General Pre-Activity (APS): 4–6 days (SLIFE 5–8 days if cross-org) |\r\n| Project 7 | Freelancing & Part-Time Work Seminar | General Pre-Activity (APS): 4–6 days (Possible OCCS SLIFE overlap) |\r\n| Project 4 | Laboratory Accessibility Audit walkthrough | Letters and Requests: 2–3 days |\r\n| Project 8 | Fundraiser Events (Local Business Collab) | SAS (SCT): 1–3 days (+ External MOA: 14 days) |\r\n\r\n## Bucket B — Standing Platform Features (Requires P&M / GOSM Clearance)\r\nThese items are platform features, websites, portals, or registries. They require **Publicity Materials (P&M) approval (24 Hours lead time)** before any announcements, along with GOSM posting clearance. *Note: Disbursing funds requires a SAS.*\r\n\r\n| Project | Sub-Project / Feature | Documentation Type & Lead Time |\r\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\r\n| Project 1 | Research Grants & Funding Portal | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 1 | Research Job Board | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 1 | Research Readiness Survey | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 1 | Scholarship Grade Calculator | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 1 | Academic Pathing Tool | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 1 | Syllabus Transparency Portal | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 1 | Shared Flashcard Library | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 1 | Free Software Directory | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 1 | LaTeX tutorials | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 1 | NMAT Online Repository | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 3 | Centralized Grievance Channel | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 3 | Financial Transparency Ledger | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 3 | Student Rights Charter | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 3 | Suggestion Tab | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 4 | Women and Minority in STEM (Archive) | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 5 | Shanghay Laya Website | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 5 | Queer Identity Science Forum | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 5 | Pre-Colonial Gender & Trans History Session | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 6 | Food Security Pantry | P&M: 24 Hours (+ SAS: 1–3 days for funds) |\r\n| Project 6 | Emergency Micro-Grant Fund | P&M: 24 Hours (+ SAS: 1–3 days for funds) |\r\n| Project 6 | Welfare Outreach Registry | P&M: 24 Hours |\r\n| Project 7 | Equipment & Apparel Exchange | P&M: 24 Hours |\n"},{"filename":"00_Project_Defense_Briefing.md","name":"Project Defense Briefing","content":"# Project Defense Briefing\r\n\r\n## P1: Student Resource Hub\r\n- **Elevator Pitch:** A centralized digital infrastructure that removes systemic barriers to academic progression and research funding.\r\n- **Hardest FAQ:** How will you keep this updated when the curriculum and scholarships constantly change?\r\n- **Panel Follow-Up (Sustainability):** *Answer:* We built this on open-source, easily transferable static sites, eliminating long-term maintenance costs and making turnovers seamless.\r\n\r\n## P2: Semana ng Siyensya (COS Week)\r\n- **Elevator Pitch:** A week-long academic and gaming celebration that directly funds the Food Security Pantry and Emergency Micro-Grants through merchandise drives.\r\n- **Hardest FAQ:** How will you ensure the academic competitions don't interfere with students' classes?\r\n- **Panel Follow-Up (Incentivization):** *Answer:* We are currently coordinating with faculty to provide academic incentives (e.g., extra credit) to encourage participation without adding burden.\r\n\r\n## P3: Transparency Platform\r\n- **Elevator Pitch:** A platform holding the council to the same rigorous accountability standards it demands from the administration.\r\n- **Hardest FAQ:** How do you guarantee the council won't just cover up grievances filed against its own officers?\r\n- **Panel Follow-Up (Legal Exposure):** *Answer:* We employ strict moderation guidelines and a 2-officer approval requirement before hiding any personal attacks on the Suggestion Tab, protecting students and officers alike.\r\n\r\n## P4: Inclusion, Accessibility & Representation\r\n- **Elevator Pitch:** Moving beyond performative awareness by demanding structural, physical, and historical accessibility in the College of Science.\r\n- **Hardest FAQ:** What happens if the administration completely ignores your Laboratory Accessibility Audit?\r\n- **Panel Follow-Up (FSL Costs):** *Answer:* Solved via a formal MOA with a Deaf community organization, ensuring professional, sustained instruction rather than relying on one-off volunteers.\r\n\r\n## P5: Queer & Trans Education Series\r\n- **Elevator Pitch:** Rooting queer and trans identities in rigorous biological, sociological, and historical research to counter unscientific prejudice.\r\n- **Hardest FAQ:** What if the Shanghay Laya website provides dangerous medical advice?\r\n- **Panel Follow-Up (Admin Pushback):** *Answer:* Defended via the Student Rights Charter and our strict reliance on credentialed, peer-reviewed academics.\r\n\r\n## P6: Student Emergency Response\r\n- **Elevator Pitch:** A rapid-response crisis ecosystem that aggressively cuts through bureaucracy to deliver aid when students need it most.\r\n- **Hardest FAQ:** Why isn't the pantry logging names to prevent hoarding?\r\n- **Panel Follow-Up (Data Privacy):** *Answer:* The Welfare Registry complies strictly with RA 10173; it is opt-in only, and we enforce a mandatory termly data wipe.\r\n\r\n## P7: Financial Empowerment Initiative\r\n- **Elevator Pitch:** Directly mitigating the hidden costs of a science degree through resource sharing and freelancing upskilling.\r\n- **Hardest FAQ:** Is the Student Council endorsing the freelancing platforms mentioned in the seminar?\r\n- **Panel Follow-Up (Quality Control):** *Answer:* The Equipment Exchange mandates basic condition checks and features a clear \"No Implied Warranty\" disclaimer.\r\n\r\n## P8: Fundraising & Local Business\r\n- **Elevator Pitch:** Transforming mutual community support into sustainable, reliable financial aid for the Emergency Fund and Research Grants Pool.\r\n- **Hardest FAQ:** What if we don't get any partners and the fair gets cancelled? Does the Emergency Fund run out?\r\n- **Panel Follow-Up (Proceeds Transparency):** *Answer:* We enforce a strict 70/30 split tracked visibly on the Project 3 public Ledger.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## Contingency Question\r\n**Q: \"If you had to cut one project due to budget or time constraints, which one and why?\"**\r\n**A:** \"We would reluctantly cut the *Pre-Colonial Gender & Trans History Session (Project 5)*. While highly valuable, our absolute, non-negotiable priority is immediate student survival and welfare. We will never compromise the Emergency Response Program (P6), the Transparency Platform (P3), or the Resource Hub (P1). If necessary, the history session's insights can be integrated into the Science Forum so we can preserve resources for direct aid.\"\r\n"},{"filename":"00_Risk_Register.md","name":"Risk Register","content":"# Risk Register\r\n\r\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation | Owner |\r\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\r\n| **P1: Scholarship Criteria Changes** | High | High | ADSO point of contact established; criteria verified termly. | Dir. Academics |\r\n| **P1: Syllabus LOA Rejected** | Medium | High | Secure physical/digital signature from Dean early before launch. | Dir. Academics |\r\n| **P2: Low Event Turnout** | Medium | Medium | Heavy promotions, coordinate for faculty incentives (extra credit). | Dir. Academics |\r\n| **P2: Merch Sales Miss Targets** | Medium | High | Pre-order system to avoid overstocking and guarantee profit margins. | Dir. Finance |\r\n| **P3: Admin Ignores Grievance** | High | Medium | Only promise visibility. Document unresolved cases publicly (with consent). | Dir. Stud. Services |\r\n| **P3: Suggestion Tab Toxicity** | High | Low | 2-officer approval required to moderate personal attacks; policy criticisms stay. | Dir. Stud. Services |\r\n| **P4: FSL MOA Fails** | Low | High | External MOA negotiated early. Will not rely on single volunteer. | Dir. EXT/INT |\r\n| **P4: Lab Audit Access Denied** | Medium | Medium | 90-day deadline established. Publish audit publicly if ignored. | Dir. Advocacy |\r\n| **P4: STEM Archive Privacy Breach**| Low | High | Strict RA 10173 opt-in consent form mandated prior to posting. | Dir. Advocacy |\r\n| **P5: Unqualified Speaker** | Low | High | Strict vetting: only academic/peer-reviewed researchers invited. | Dir. Advocacy |\r\n| **P5: Legal Liability (Hormones)** | Medium | High | Legal disclaimer review dependency; link only to licensed endocrinologists. | Dir. Advocacy |\r\n| **P6: Calamity Trigger Ambiguity** | Low | Medium | Strict reliance on PAGASA / LGU declarations for Tier 3/4. | Dir. Finance |\r\n| **P6: Welfare Registry Privacy Leak**| Low | Critical | RA 10173 compliance. Data wiped termly unless re-consented. | Dir. Stud. Services |\r\n| **P7: Faulty Donated Equipment** | Medium | Low | Mandatory basic condition check; explicit \"No Implied Warranty\" disclaimer. | Dir. Stud. Services |\r\n| **P7: Misconstrued Endorsement** | Low | High | Verbal and visual disclaimers stating \"Lived Experience, No Endorsement.\" | President |\r\n| **P8: Partner Backs Out Mid-Term** | Medium | High | Rely on minimum 3-5 partners to dilute risk. | Dir. EXT/INT |\r\n| **P8: Zero Partners Secured (Plan B)**| Low | High | Publicly acknowledge shortfall; launch Emergency Crowdfunding Drive. | Dir. EXT/INT |\r\n| **General: Pre-Act Rejected Near Blackout**| Medium | High | Buffer lead times factored in. If rejected, move to Post-Midterms or Post-ILW. | Dir. Documentations |\r\n| **General: Officer Turnover Mid-Term**| Low | High | Strict Handover Notes and centralized execution plans ensure continuity. | Chief of Staff |\r\n"}]};